{"title_page": "Eastern Highlands", "text_new": ":''\"Eastern Highlands\" also refers to [[Eastern Highlands Province]] in Papua New Guinea, and part of the [[Great Dividing Range]], [[Australia]].''\n[[Image:Eastern higlands fromnyanga.jpg|thumb|300px|Northern part of the Eastern Highlands range as seen from Nyanga town.]]\n[[File:Eastern Highlands Nyanga.jpg|thumb|Eastern Highlands looking south towards Nyanga.]]\n[[File:Mt. Mozi.jpg|thumb|Mt. Mozi is a prominent peak at the Northern end of the range.]]\n\nThe '''Eastern Highlands''', also known as the '''Manica Highlands''', is a [[mountain range]] in eastern [[Zimbabwe]]. The Eastern Highlands extend for about {{convert|300|km|mi}} along Zimbabwe's eastern border with [[Mozambique]].<ref name=\"EnZim\">{{cite book|title=Encyclopedia Zimbabwe|publisher=Arlington Business Corporation|location=Worcester|date=1989|edition=2nd|isbn=0-9514505-0-6}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nThe range comprises three main mountain groups. The [[Nyanga, Zimbabwe|Nyanga Mountains]] to the north contain Zimbabwe's highest mountain [[Mount Nyangani]], [[Africa]]'s second-longest waterfall [[Mutarazi Falls]], and the [[Honde Valley]] which leads into Mozambique. The [[Bvumba Mountains]] are centrally situated near the city of [[Mutare]]. The [[Chimanimani Mountains]] lie to the south. These mountains are all sparsely populated highland country, and are covered in rich grassland and forests.<ref name=\"EnZim\" />\n\n[[Mutare]] is the largest city in the highlands, located in Zimbabwe in the saddle between the Nyanga and Bvumba mountains. \n\nThe main east-west road through the highlands is the [[R5 road (Zimbabwe)|A3]] (Zimbabwe) - N6 (Mozambique), which which connects the port of [[Beira, Mozambique|Beira]] in Mozambique to Zimbabwe's capital [[Harare]] via [[Chimoio]], [[Manica, Mozambique|Manica]], and Mutare, with a border crossing at [[Machipanda]]. The [[Beira\u2013Bulawayo railway]] also crosses the highlands at Machipanda.\n\nThe Eastern Highlands are part of the '''East African Highlands''', one of four distinct physiographic divisions on the African continent. The East African Highlands physiographic division consists of the [[East African Rift]] and [[Ethiopian Highlands|Abyssinian]] physiographic provinces, part of the long chain of mountains that runs down [[East Africa]]. The mountains and mountain ranges that make up the East African Highlands share many common plant and animal species and communities, known as [[Afromontane]] flora and fauna.\n\n==Climate==\nThe Highlands have a more equable climate than Zimbabwe's central plateau, with higher rainfall, low cloud and heavy mists and dew as moisture moves inland from the [[Indian Ocean]]. Many streams and rivers originate in these mountains. The northern portion is drained by tributaries of the  [[Zambezi River]], while the southern portion is drained by tributaries of the [[Save River (Africa)|Save River]].<ref name=\"worldwildlife.org\">\"Eastern Zimbabwe montane forest-grassland mosaic\". World Wildlife Fund. Accessed 17 June 2018 [https://www.worldwildlife.org/ecoregions/at1006]</ref> The eastern slope is drained by Mozambique's [[Buzi River (Mozambique)|Buzi]] and [[Pungwe River|Pungwe]] rivers.\n\n==Eastern Zimbabwe montane forest-grassland mosaic==\nThe Highlands are home to the '''Eastern Zimbabwe montane forest-grassland mosaic''' [[ecoregion]]. The ecoregion includes the portion of the Higlands above 1000 meters elevation, including the Inyangani Highlands, Vumba Highlands, Chimanimani Mountains, Chipinge Uplands, and the isolated [[Mount Gorongosa]] further east in Mozambique. The [[Southern Miombo woodlands]] ecoregion lies at lower elevations east and west of the highlands.<ref name=\"worldwildlife.org\"/>\n\nThe highlands have a cooler, moister climate than the surrounding lowlands, which support distinct communities of plants and animals. The ecoregion is home to several plant communities: submontane and montane grasslands, moist evergreen forest, dry montane forest, miombo woodlands, and [[heathland]]s.<ref name=\"worldwildlife.org\"/>\n\n==Flora==\nMuch of the small area consists of rolling hills covered with grassland, which are renewed annually following the fires that occur at the end of the dry season. At lower elevations, ''[[Themeda triandra]]'' is the predominant grass on the more fertile red soils, and ''[[Loudetia simplex]]'' is common on less-fertile white sandy soils. At higher elevations are montane grasslands made up mostly of short, tufted grasses, including ''[[Loudetia simplex]], [[Trachypogon spicatus]], [[Exotheca abyssinica]],'' and ''[[Monocymbium ceresiiforme]]''.<ref name=\"worldwildlife.org\"/>\n\nSome valleys and east-facing slopes contain areas of tropical rainforest, with a high canopy, [[liana]]s, and a rich undergrowth. There are larger areas of dry forest at higher altitudes in places where the ground is well watered and on drier slopes patches of [[miombo]] woodland ''([[Brachystegia spiciformis]]'', ''[[Brachystegia tamarindoides]]'' and ''[[Uapaca kirkiana]]'') and areas of heathland at higher elevations. There are patches of the tall evergreen Mobola Plum ''[[Parinari curatellifolia]]'' near the town of [[Chipinge]] and on the western slopes of the Nyanga Highlands.\n\nIn the Chimanimani Mountains and [[Mount Gorongosa]], heathlands are found on poor, acidic sandy soils derived from [[quartzite]]. The heathlands are of two types, [[Ericaceae|ericaceous]] and [[proteaceous]]. The ericaceous heathlands are dominated by ''Philippia pallidiflora, P. hexandra, Phylica ericoides, Passerina montana, Erica eylesii, E. pleiotricha, E. gazensis,'' and ''E. johnstoniana. Protea gazensis, P. welwitschii'', and ''[[Leucospermum saxosum]]'' are common in the proteaceous heathlands.<ref name=\"worldwildlife.org\"/>\n\nA number of indigenous monocot lilies with small distribution ranges occur in the highlands. ''Cryptostephanotis vansonii'', ''Cyrtanthus rhodesianus'', and ''Scadoxus pole-evansi'' are popular with rare plant collectors.\n\n==Fauna==\nThis variety of different types of habitat results in a richness of animal life too. Animals found in the highlands include [[blue monkey]] ''(Cercopithecus mitis)'' [[Sykes' monkey]] ''(Cercopithecus albogularis)'', [[East African little collared fruit bat]] ''(Myonycteris relicta)'' and [[Marshall's pygmy chameleon]] ''([[Rhampholeon]] marshalli)''. Many of these animals are found throughout East Africa.<ref>{{WWF ecoregion|id=at1006|name=Eastern Zimbabwe montane forest-grassland mosaic}}</ref>\n\nThe highlands are also rich in birdlife<ref>Ian Sinclair, Birds of Southern Africa, Struik Publishers 1996</ref> including [[trumpeter hornbill]] ''(Bycanistes bucinator)'', [[Knysna turaco]] ''(Tauraco corythaix)'', [[purple-crested turaco]] ''(Tauraco porphyreolophus)'', [[crested guineafowl]] ''(Guttera pucherani)'' and [[crowned eagle]] ''(Stephanoaetus coronatus)''. Two species, the [[Chirinda apalis]] ''(Apalis chirindensis)'' and [[Roberts's warbler]] ''(Oreophilais robertsi)'', are endemic to the Eastern Highlands. The Chirinda apalis lives deep in the evergreen forests, while Roberts's warbler inhabits the forest edge.<ref name=\"worldwildlife.org\"/>\n\nThe forests are also full of butterflies, most notably [[Papilio|swallowtails]] such as the emperor swallowtail ''([[Papilio ophidicephalus]])'' and the citrus swallowtail ''([[Papilio demodocus]])'' and the forest undergrowth in particular shelters a variety of reptiles including [[skink]]s, [[gecko]]s, [[lizard]]s, [[frog]]s, [[toad]]s, and [[snake]]s.\n{{See also|Reptiles and frogs of the Eastern Highlands}}\n\n==Threats and preservation==\nThe mountain forests are vulnerable to logging and the grasslands susceptible to fire and the rainforests, which by definition grow on well-watered fertile land, to clearance for agriculture. The moist climate is ideal for planting tea, coffee and hardwoods. However, much of the original vegetation remains, especially at higher altitudes, which are not suitable for farming. \n\nLarge areas of the highlands are protected, including [[Nyanga National Park]] in the Nyanga Mountains, [[Bunga Forest Botanical Reserve]] in the Bvumba Mountains, and Zimbabwe's 171km<sup>2</sup> [[Chimanimani National Park]] and Mozambique's [[Chimanimani National Reserve]] in the Chimanimani Mountains. The Chimanimani park and reserve together form the core of the Chimanimani Transfrontier Conservation Area.\n\n==External Links==\n* [https://www.worldwildlife.org/ecoregions/at1006|Eastern Zimbabwe montane forest-grassland mosaic (terrestrial ecoregion)]\n* [https://www.feow.org/ecoregions/details/563|Eastern Zimbabwe Highlands (freshwater ecoregion)]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{coord|18.723|S|32.842|E|type:country|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Afromontane ecoregions]]\n[[Category:Afrotropic ecoregions]]\n[[Category:Eastern Zimbabwe montane forest-grassland mosaic]]\n[[Category:Ecoregions of Mozambique]]\n[[Category:Ecoregions of Zimbabwe]]\n[[Category:Great Rift Valley]]\n[[Category:Highlands]]\n[[Category:Montane grasslands and shrublands]]\n[[Category:Mountains of Zimbabwe]]\n[[Category:Mountain ranges of Mozambique]]\n[[Category:Physiographic divisions]]\n", "text_old": ":''\"Eastern Highlands\" also refers to [[Eastern Highlands Province]] in Papua New Guinea, and part of the [[Great Dividing Range]], [[Australia]].''\n[[Image:Eastern higlands fromnyanga.jpg|thumb|300px|Northern part of the Eastern Highlands range as seen from Nyanga town.]]\n[[File:Eastern Highlands Nyanga.jpg|thumb|Eastern Highlands looking south towards Nyanga.]]\n[[File:Mt. Mozi.jpg|thumb|Mt. Mozi is a prominent peak at the Northern end of the range.]]\n\nThe '''Eastern Highlands''', also known as the '''Manica Highlands''', is a [[mountain range]] in eastern [[Zimbabwe]]. The Eastern Highlands extend for about {{convert|300|km|mi}} along Zimbabwe's eastern border with [[Mozambique]].<ref name=\"EnZim\">{{cite book|title=Encyclopedia Zimbabwe|publisher=Arlington Business Corporation|location=Worcester|date=1989|edition=2nd|isbn=0-9514505-0-6}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nThe range comprises three main mountain groups. The [[Nyanga, Zimbabwe|Nyanga Mountains]] to the north contain Zimbabwe's highest mountain [[Mount Nyangani]], [[Africa]]'s second-longest waterfall [[Mutarazi Falls]], and the [[Honde Valley]] which leads into Mozambique. The [[Bvumba Mountains]] are centrally situated near the city of [[Mutare]]. The [[Chimanimani Mountains]] lie to the south. These mountains are all sparsely populated highland country, and are covered in rich grassland and forests.<ref name=\"EnZim\" />\n\n[[Mutare]] is the largest city in the highlands, located in Zimbabwe between the Nyanga and Bvumba mountains. \n\nThe main east-west road through the highlands is the [[R5 road (Zimbabwe)|A3]] (Zimbabwe) - N6 (Mozambique), which which connects the port of [[Beira, Mozambique|Beira]] in Mozambique to Zimbabwe's capital Harare via [[Chimoio]], [[Manica]], and Mutare, with a border crossing at [[Machipanda]]. The [[Beira\u2013Bulawayo railway]] also crosses the highlans at Machipanda.\n\nThe Eastern Highlands are part of the '''East African Highlands''', one of four distinct physiographic divisions on the African continent. The East African Highlands physiographic division consists of the [[East African Rift]] and [[Ethiopian Highlands|Abyssinian]] physiographic provinces, part of the long chain of mountains that runs down [[East Africa]]. The mountains and mountain ranges that make up the East African Highlands share many common plant and animal species and communities, known as [[Afromontane]] flora and fauna.\n\n==Climate==\nThe Highlands have a more equable climate than Zimbabwe's central plateau, with higher rainfall, low cloud and heavy mists and dew as moisture moves inland from the [[Indian Ocean]]. Many streams and rivers originate in these mountains. The northern portion is drained by tributaries of the  [[Zambezi River]], while the southern portion is drained by tributaries of the [[Save River (Africa)|Save River]].<ref name=\"worldwildlife.org\">\"Eastern Zimbabwe montane forest-grassland mosaic\". World Wildlife Fund. Accessed 17 June 2018 [https://www.worldwildlife.org/ecoregions/at1006]</ref> The eastern slope is drained by Mozambique's [[Buzi River (Mozambique)|Buzi]] and [[Pungwe River|Pungwe]] rivers.\n\n==Eastern Zimbabwe montane forest-grassland mosaic==\nThe Highlands are home to the '''Eastern Zimbabwe montane forest-grassland mosaic''' [[ecoregion]]. The ecoregion includes the portion of the Higlands above 1000 meters elevation, including the Inyangani Highlands, Vumba Highlands, Chimanimani Mountains, Chipinge Uplands, and the isolated [[Mount Gorongosa]] further east in Mozambique. The [[Southern Miombo woodlands]] ecoregion lies at lower elevations east and west of the highlands.<ref name=\"worldwildlife.org\"/>\n\nThe highlands have a cooler, moister climate than the surrounding lowlands, which support distinct communities of plants and animals. The ecoregion is home to several plant communities: submontane and montane grasslands, moist evergreen forest, dry montane forest, miombo woodlands, and [[heathland]]s.<ref name=\"worldwildlife.org\"/>\n\n==Flora==\nMuch of the small area consists of rolling hills covered with grassland, which are renewed annually following the fires that occur at the end of the dry season. At lower elevations, ''[[Themeda triandra]]'' is the predominant grass on the more fertile red soils, and ''[[Loudetia simplex]]'' is common on less-fertile white sandy soils. At higher elevations are montane grasslands made up mostly of short, tufted grasses, including ''[[Loudetia simplex]], [[Trachypogon spicatus]], [[Exotheca abyssinica]],'' and ''[[Monocymbium ceresiiforme]]''.<ref name=\"worldwildlife.org\"/>\n\nSome valleys and east-facing slopes contain areas of tropical rainforest, with a high canopy, [[liana]]s, and a rich undergrowth. There are larger areas of dry forest at higher altitudes in places where the ground is well watered and on drier slopes patches of [[miombo]] woodland ''([[Brachystegia spiciformis]]'', ''[[Brachystegia tamarindoides]]'' and ''[[Uapaca kirkiana]]'') and areas of heathland at higher elevations. There are patches of the tall evergreen Mobola Plum ''[[Parinari curatellifolia]]'' near the town of [[Chipinge]] and on the western slopes of the Nyanga Highlands.\n\nIn the Chimanimani Mountains and [[Mount Gorongosa]], heathlands are found on poor, acidic sandy soils derived from [[quartzite]]. The heathlands are of two types, [[Ericaceae|ericaceous]] and [[proteaceous]]. The ericaceous heathlands are dominated by ''Philippia pallidiflora, P. hexandra, Phylica ericoides, Passerina montana, Erica eylesii, E. pleiotricha, E. gazensis,'' and ''E. johnstoniana. Protea gazensis, P. welwitschii'', and ''[[Leucospermum saxosum]]'' are common in the proteaceous heathlands.<ref name=\"worldwildlife.org\"/>\n\nA number of indigenous monocot lilies with small distribution ranges occur in the highlands. ''Cryptostephanotis vansonii'', ''Cyrtanthus rhodesianus'', and ''Scadoxus pole-evansi'' are popular with rare plant collectors.\n\n==Fauna==\nThis variety of different types of habitat results in a richness of animal life too. Animals found in the highlands include [[blue monkey]] ''(Cercopithecus mitis)'' [[Sykes' monkey]] ''(Cercopithecus albogularis)'', [[East African little collared fruit bat]] ''(Myonycteris relicta)'' and [[Marshall's pygmy chameleon]] ''([[Rhampholeon]] marshalli)''. Many of these animals are found throughout East Africa.<ref>{{WWF ecoregion|id=at1006|name=Eastern Zimbabwe montane forest-grassland mosaic}}</ref>\n\nThe highlands are also rich in birdlife<ref>Ian Sinclair, Birds of Southern Africa, Struik Publishers 1996</ref> including [[trumpeter hornbill]] ''(Bycanistes bucinator)'', [[Knysna turaco]] ''(Tauraco corythaix)'', [[purple-crested turaco]] ''(Tauraco porphyreolophus)'', [[crested guineafowl]] ''(Guttera pucherani)'' and [[crowned eagle]] ''(Stephanoaetus coronatus)''. Two species, the [[Chirinda apalis]] ''(Apalis chirindensis)'' and [[Roberts's warbler]] ''(Oreophilais robertsi)'', are endemic to the Eastern Highlands. The Chirinda apalis lives deep in the evergreen forests, while Roberts's warbler inhabits the forest edge.<ref name=\"worldwildlife.org\"/>\n\nThe forests are also full of butterflies, most notably [[Papilio|swallowtails]] such as the emperor swallowtail ''([[Papilio ophidicephalus]])'' and the citrus swallowtail ''([[Papilio demodocus]])'' and the forest undergrowth in particular shelters a variety of reptiles including [[skink]]s, [[gecko]]s, [[lizard]]s, [[frog]]s, [[toad]]s, and [[snake]]s.\n{{See also|Reptiles and frogs of the Eastern Highlands}}\n\n==Threats and preservation==\nThe mountain forests are vulnerable to logging and the grasslands susceptible to fire and the rainforests, which by definition grow on well-watered fertile land, to clearance for agriculture. The moist climate is ideal for planting tea, coffee and hardwoods. However, much of the original vegetation remains, especially at higher altitudes, which are not suitable for farming. \n\nLarge areas of the highlands are protected, including [[Nyanga National Park]] in the Nyanga Mountains, [[Bunga Forest Botanical Reserve]] in the Bvumba Mountains, and Zimbabwe's 171km<sup>2</sup> [[Chimanimani National Park]] and Mozambique's [[Chimanimani National Reserve]] in the Chimanimani Mountains. The Chimanimani park and reserve together form the core of the Chimanimani Transfrontier Conservation Area.\n\n==External Links==\n* [https://www.worldwildlife.org/ecoregions/at1006|Eastern Zimbabwe montane forest-grassland mosaic (terrestrial ecoregion)]\n* [https://www.feow.org/ecoregions/details/563|Eastern Zimbabwe Highlands (freshwater ecoregion)]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{coord|18.723|S|32.842|E|type:country|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Afromontane ecoregions]]\n[[Category:Afrotropic ecoregions]]\n[[Category:Eastern Zimbabwe montane forest-grassland mosaic]]\n[[Category:Ecoregions of Mozambique]]\n[[Category:Ecoregions of Zimbabwe]]\n[[Category:Great Rift Valley]]\n[[Category:Highlands]]\n[[Category:Montane grasslands and shrublands]]\n[[Category:Mountains of Zimbabwe]]\n[[Category:Mountain ranges of Mozambique]]\n[[Category:Physiographic divisions]]\n", "name_user": "Tom Radulovich", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eGeography:disambiguate link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eastern_Highlands"}
{"title_page": "2019 Boston Red Sox season", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox MLB yearly\n| name = Boston Red Sox\n| season = 2019\n| misc = \n| image = Bosb.png\n| current league = American League\n| y1 =  1901\n| division = [[American League East|East Division]]\n| y2 =  1969\n| Uniform logo =\n| ballpark = [[Fenway Park]]\n| y4 = 1912\n| city = [[Boston]]\n| y5 = 1901\n| record = 84\u201378 (.519)\n| divisional place = 3rd\n| owners =  [[John W. Henry]] ([[Fenway Sports Group]])\n| general managers = none (de facto by President of Baseball Operations)<!-- Dombrowski never had GM as an official title -->\n| presbo = [[Dave Dombrowski]] (until Sept. 9)<ref>{{cite tweet |user=PeteAbe |number=1170912319804727296 |title=Red Sox fired Dave Dombrowski just after midnight. |date=September 9, 2019 |accessdate=September 9, 2019}}</ref><br>Acting (from Sept. 9): [[Brian O'Halloran (baseball)|Brian O'Halloran]], Eddie Romero, Zack Scott, [[Raquel Ferreira]]<ref name=InterimLeaders>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbssports.com/mlb/news/red-sox-promote-four-person-group-after-firing-dombrowski-raquel-ferreira-becomes-highest-ranking-woman-in-mlb/ |title=Red Sox promote four-person group after firing Dombrowski; Raquel Ferreira becomes highest-ranking woman in MLB |first=R.J. |last=Anderson |website=[[CBS Sports]] |date=September 9, 2019 |accessdate=October 2, 2019}}</ref>\n| managers = [[Alex Cora]]\n| television = [[New England Sports Network|NESN]]<br><small>([[Dave O'Brien (sportscaster)|Dave O'Brien]] (play-by-play); [[Jerry Remy]], [[Dennis Eckersley]], [[Carlos Pe\u00f1a]], [[Jarrod Saltalamacchia]] (color); [[Tom Caron]] (studio))</small>\n| radio = [[WEEI-FM]]<br>[[Boston Red Sox Radio Network]]<br><small>([[Joe Castiglione]] & rotation of partners)</small>\n}}\n\nThe '''2019 Boston Red Sox season''' was the 119th season in the team's history, and their 108th season at [[Fenway Park]]. The [[Boston Red Sox|Red Sox]] entered the season as reigning [[World Series]] champions, but did not repeat, as they were eliminated from the playoff race on September 20. With a record of  84\u201378 (.519), they finished third in the [[American League East]], the first time they did not win their division since [[2015 Boston Red Sox season|2015]].\n\n==Offseason==\nDuring the offseason, the team retained or re-signed most players from the [[2018 Boston Red Sox season|2018 team]]. Not retained were [[closer (baseball)|closer]] [[Craig Kimbrel]], reliever [[Joe Kelly (pitcher)|Joe Kelly]], starter [[Drew Pomeranz]], and second baseman [[Ian Kinsler]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.si.com/mlb/2019/03/27/boston-red-sox-season-preview |title=Mookie Betts, Chris Sale and the Boston Red Sox Are Looking for a Repeat |first=Emma |last=Baccellieri |website=[[Sports Illustrated]] |date=March 27, 2019 |accessdate=March 27, 2019}}</ref> Prior to [[Opening Day]], the team sent catcher [[Sandy Le\u00f3n]] to the [[Minor League Baseball|minor leagues]], opting to carry two catchers on the roster, [[Christian V\u00e1zquez]] and [[Blake Swihart]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bostonherald.com/2019/03/25/red-sox-notebook-sandy-leon-the-odd-man-out/ |title=Red Sox notebook: Sandy Leon the odd man out |first=Michael |last=Silverman |newspaper=[[Boston Herald]] |date=March 25, 2019 |accessdate=March 25, 2019}}</ref> Manager [[Alex Cora]] stated he would use [[Andrew Benintendi]] as the team's [[leadoff hitter]], with [[Mookie Betts]] batting second, swapping their positions from the team's usual 2018 batting order.<ref name=BeniLeadoff/> Cora did not name a specific relief pitcher as closer.<ref name=CoraOpeningLineup>{{cite news |url=https://www.bostonherald.com/2019/03/27/red-sox-notebook-rafael-devers-to-hit-third-alex-cora-wont-name-a-closer/ |title=Red Sox notebook: Rafael Devers to hit third, Alex Cora won\u2019t name a closer |first=Jason |last=Mastrodonato |newspaper=[[Boston Herald]] |date=March 27, 2019 |accessdate=March 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n{{collapse top|title=October 2018}}\n\n===October 2018===\n*On October 30, the Red Sox exercised their $15M 2019 team option on LHP [[Chris Sale]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Doyle|first=Ricky|url=https://nesn.com/2018/10/red-sox-pick-up-chris-sales-contract-option-for-2019-mlb-season/|title=Red Sox Pick Up Chris Sale\u2019s Contract Option For 2019 MLB Season|work=NESN.com|date=October 30, 2018|accessdate=November 27, 2018}}</ref>\n*On October 31, LHP [[David Price (baseball)|David Price]] announced that he would return to the Red Sox for the 2019 season, declining a contract option that would have allowed him to become a [[free agent]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.si.com/mlb/2018/10/31/david-price-contract-opt-in-boston-red-sox-2019-free-agency-decision |title=David Price Announces Plans to Opt In to Contract, Stay with Red Sox |first=Alaa |last=Abdeldaiem |website=[[Sports Illustrated]] |date=October 31, 2018 |accessdate=November 27, 2018}}</ref>\n{{collapse bottom}}\n\n{{collapse top|title=November 2018}}\n\n===November 2018===\n*On November 12, [[Closer (baseball)|closer]] [[Craig Kimbrel]] declined Boston's one-year, $17.9 million qualifying offer, thus becoming a free agent.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://bosoxinjection.com/2018/11/12/red-sox-closer-craig-kimbrel-rejects-qualifying-offer/ |title=Red Sox closer Craig Kimbrel rejects qualifying offer |first=Sean |last=Penney |website=bosoxinjection.com |date=November 12, 2018 |accessdate=November 27, 2018}}</ref>\n*On November 15, the Red Sox announced an average price increase of 2.5 percent for tickets to 2019 games.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://boston.cbslocal.com/2018/11/15/red-sox-raise-ticket-prices-2019-season-fenway-park-mlb/ |title=Red Sox Raise Ticket Prices For 2019 Season |website=[[WBZ-TV|cbslocal.com]] |date=November 15, 2018 |accessdate=November 27, 2018}}</ref>\n*On November 16, the Red Sox re-signed 1B/LF [[Steve Pearce (baseball)|Steve Pearce]] to a one-year, $6.25M deal.<ref>{{cite web|last=London|first=Adam|url=https://nesn.com/2018/11/red-sox-re-sign-2018-world-series-mvp-steve-pearce-to-one-year-deal/|title=Red Sox Re-Sign 2018 World Series MVP Steve Pearce To One-Year Deal|work=NESN.com|date=November 16, 2018|accessdate=November 27, 2018}}</ref>\n*On November 20, the Padres traded RHP [[Colten Brewer]] to the Red Sox for infielder [[Esteban Quiroz]].<ref name=NESN20Nov>{{cite news |url=https://nesn.com/2018/11/red-sox-perform-slew-of-roster-moves-make-colten-brewer-trade-official/ |title=Red Sox Perform Slew Of Roster Moves, Make Colten Brewer Trade Official |first=Logan |last=Mullen |website=[[New England Sports Network|NESN]] |date=November 20, 2018 |accessdate=December 11, 2018}}</ref> On the same day, the Red Sox released RHP [[William Cuevas]], who then signed with the [[KT Wiz]] of Korea's [[KBO League]].<ref name=NESN20Nov/>\n*On November 28, senior vice president of player personnel [[Allard Baird]] was hired by the [[New York Mets]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/sports/redsox/2018/11/28/red-sox-executive-allard-baird-hired-away-mets/ogUn07idBaepNDUFKOWobJ/story.html |title=Red Sox executive Allard Baird hired away by Mets |first=Peter |last=Abraham |newspaper=[[The Boston Globe]] |url-access=limited |date=November 28, 2018|accessdate=November 28, 2018}}</ref>\n*On November 30, the Red Sox re-signed RHP [[Tyler Thornburg]] to a one-year contract worth $1.75 million, plus incentives worth up to $400,000.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/sports/redsox/2018/11/30/red-sox-avoid-arbitration-with-tyler-thornburg-sign-him-one-year-deal/6JywZJPAj8vmkTIvDTkR6M/story.html |title=Red Sox avoid arbitration with Tyler Thornburg, sign him to one-year deal |first=Peter |last=Abraham |newspaper=[[The Boston Globe]] |url-access=limited |date=November 30, 2018|accessdate=November 30, 2018}}</ref>\n{{collapse bottom}}\n\n{{collapse top|title=December 2018}}\n\n===December 2018===\n* On December 6, the Red Sox re-signed RHP [[Nathan Eovaldi]] to a four-year contract, reportedly worth $67.5 million.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2803922-nathan-eovaldi-red-sox-reportedly-agree-to-4-year-contract-in-free-agency |title=Nathan Eovaldi, Red Sox Agree to 4-Year Contract Reportedly Worth $67.5M |first=Mike |last=Chiari |website=[[Bleacher Report]] |date=December 6, 2018 |accessdate=December 11, 2018}}</ref>\n* On December 10, the Cincinnati Reds claimed LHP [[Robby Scott]] off of [[waivers (baseball)|waivers]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.daytondailynews.com/sports/cincinnati-reds-add-relief-pitcher-waivers-from-red-sox/VbiiqNhU2S6SQcBNg0TP4J/ |title=Cincinnati Reds claim relief pitcher on waivers from Red Sox |first=John |last=Boyle |website=[[Dayton Daily News]] |date=December 10, 2018 |accessdate=December 11, 2018}}</ref>\n* On December 11, radio announcer [[Tim Neverett]] advised that he allowed his contract with [[WEEI-FM]] to run out and that he would no longer be part of the Red Sox radio broadcast team.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.boston.com/sports/boston-red-sox/2018/12/11/tim-neverett-will-not-return-to-the-red-sox-radio-broadcast-team |title=Tim Neverett will not return to the Red Sox radio broadcast team |first=Chad |last=Finn |website=[[Boston.com]] |date=December 11, 2018 |accessdate=December 11, 2018}}</ref>\n* On December 11, manager [[Alex Cora]] announced that [[Andrew Benintendi]] would be the team's [[leadoff hitter]] in 2019, with [[Mookie Betts]] batting second.<ref name=BeniLeadoff>{{cite news |url=https://www.boston.com/sports/boston-red-sox/2018/12/11/red-sox-al-mvp-mookie-betts-second-slot-hit |title=Red Sox moving Mookie Betts from leadoff to second slot |first=Ben |last=Walker |agency=[[Associated Press|AP]] |website=[[Boston.com]] |date=December 11, 2018 |accessdate=December 12, 2018}}</ref>\n* On December 21, the Red Sox re-signed RHP [[Heath Hembree]] to a one-year, $1.3 million deal.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://nesn.com/2018/12/red-sox-heath-hembree-avoid-arbitration-agree-to-one-year-deal/ |title=Red Sox, Heath Hembree Avoid Arbitration, Agree To One-Year Deal |first=Michael |last=McMahon |website=[[New England Sports Network|NESN]] |date=December 21, 2018 |accessdate=December 21, 2018}}</ref>\n* On December 21, RHP [[Joe Kelly (pitcher)|Joe Kelly]] signed a three-year, $27 million contract with the [[Los Angeles Dodgers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mlbtraderumors.com/2018/12/dodgers-close-to-deal-with-joe-kelly.html|title=Dodgers Sign Joe Kelly|work=MLB Trade Rumors|first=Mark|last=Polishuk|date=December 21, 2018|accessdate=December 21, 2018}}</ref>\n{{collapse bottom}}\n\n{{collapse top|title=January 2019}}\n\n===January 2019===\n* On January 10, multiple non-roster invitees to spring training were announced, including [[Rusney Castillo]], [[Josh Ockimey]], and [[Mike Shawaryn]].<ref name=JanTrans/>\n* On January 11, RHP [[Steven Wright (baseball)|Steven Wright]] agreed to a one-year contract with the Red Sox worth $1.375 million.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.espn.com/mlb/story/_/id/25732898/steven-wright-boston-red-sox-agree-1-year-contract |title=Steven Wright agrees with Red Sox on one-year contract |agency=[[Associated Press|AP]] |website=[[ESPN]] |date=January 11, 2019 |accessdate=January 11, 2019}}</ref>\n* On January 12, it was announced that the Red Sox reached agreement on one-year contracts with all of their remaining arbitration-eligible players, including [[Mookie Betts]], [[Xander Bogaerts]], [[Jackie Bradley Jr.]], and [[Brock Holt]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.boston.com/sports/boston-red-sox/2019/01/12/red-sox-player-contract-updates |title=Red Sox agree to terms with 10 players on one-year contracts |agency=[[Associated Press|AP]] |website=[[Boston.com]] |date=January 12, 2019 |accessdate=January 12, 2019}}</ref>\n* On January 30, the team signed RHP [[Jenrry Mej\u00eda]] to a minor league contract.<ref name=JanTrans>{{cite web |url=http://m.redsox.mlb.com/roster/transactions/2019/01 |title=Transactions |website=[[MLB.com]] |date=January 2019 |accessdate=February 3, 2019}}</ref> Mej\u00eda was reinstated after spending three years out of baseball due to a permanent suspension for three failed drug tests.<ref>{{cite web|last=Fish |first=Erin |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/mlb-reinstates-pitcher-jenrry-mejia-c284514412 |title=MLB reinstates pitcher Jenrry Mej\u00eda |website=[[MLB.com]] |date=July 6, 2018 |accessdate=July 7, 2018}}</ref>\n* On January 31, pitcher [[David Price (baseball)|David Price]] announced that he was changing his uniform number from 24 to 10.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbssports.com/mlb/news/david-price-will-be-wearing-a-new-number-for-the-red-sox-in-2019/ |title=David Price will be wearing a new number for the Red Sox in 2019 |first=Pete |last=Blackburn |website=[[CBS Sports]] |date=January 31, 2019 |accessdate=March 28, 2019}}</ref>\n{{collapse bottom}}\n\n{{collapse top|title=February 2019}}\n\n===February 2019===\n* \"Truck Day\"\u2014when equipment for [[spring training]] leaves Fenway Park\u2014was February 4.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://boston.cbslocal.com/2019/02/04/red-sox-truck-day-has-arrived-spring-training-fort-myers-fenway-park-mlb/ |title=\u2018Truck Day\u2019 Is Here: Red Sox Equipment Truck Set For Trek To Fort Myers |website=[[WBZ-TV]] |date=February 4, 2019 |accessdate=February 4, 2019}}</ref>\n* On February 13, spring training began for pitchers and catchers.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://weei.radio.com/blogs/weei/photos-boston-red-sox-pitchers-and-catchers-open-2019-spring-training |title=\nPhotos: Red Sox pitchers and catchers open spring training |website=[[WEEI-FM]] |date=February 13, 2019 |accessdate=February 15, 2019}}</ref>\n* On February 14, [[Entercom]] and [[WEEI-FM]] announced that a rotation of commentators would be used to replace [[Tim Neverett]] in Red Sox radio broadcasts with [[Joe Castiglione]]; included in the announcement were [[Sean McDonough]], [[Chris Berman]], and former [[Detroit Tigers]] announcer [[Mario Impemba]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.boston.com/sports/media/2019/02/14/entercom-weei-red-sox-broadcast |title=Entercom, WEEI release details on Red Sox broadcast for the 2019 season |first=Tommy |last=McArdle |website=[[Boston.com]] |date=February 14, 2019 |accessdate=February 15, 2019}}</ref>\n* On February 18, the team held its first full-squad workout.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mlb.com/redsox/video/cora-welcomes-2019-sox-to-camp-c2522803783 |title=Cora welcomes 2019 Sox to camp |website=[[MLB.com]] |date=February 18, 2019 |accessdate=February 18, 2019}}</ref>\n* On February 20, [[New England Sports Network]] (NESN) announced that [[Dennis Eckersley]] and [[Jerry Remy]] would be the usual color commentators for television broadcasts with [[Dave O'Brien (sportscaster)|Dave O'Brien]], including 30 games with a three-man booth. For games when Eckersley and Remy are not available, former Red Sox players [[Carlos Pe\u00f1a]] and [[Jarrod Saltalamacchia]] would fill in. [[Tom Caron]] continues as studio host of pregame and postgame shows, working with several other former players, including [[Jim Rice]] and [[Steve Lyons (baseball)|Steve Lyons]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.boston.com/sports/boston-red-sox/2019/02/20/nesn-will-use-the-three-man-booth-on-30-red-sox-games-this-season |title=NESN will use the three-man booth on 30 Red Sox games this season |website=[[The Boston Globe]] |via=[[Boston.com]] |date=February 20, 2019 |accessdate=February 20, 2019}}</ref>\n* On February 21, baseball writer [[Nick Cafardo]] of ''[[The Boston Globe]]'' died at JetBlue Park, reportedly of an [[embolism]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.boston.com/sports/boston-red-sox/2019/02/21/nick-cafardo-dies-at-62 |title=Veteran Globe baseball writer Nick Cafardo dies at 62 |newspaper=[[The Boston Globe]] |via=[[Boston.com]] |date=February 21, 2019 |accessdate=February 21, 2019}}</ref>\n* On February 22, the Red Sox defeated the [[Northeastern Huskies baseball|Northeastern Huskies]], 6\u20130, in a seven inning exhibition game.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/sports/redsox/2019/02/22/red-sox-get-back-into-game-action-and-beat-northeastern/4PUCILETOWnGWoqS3EV2iM/story.html?p1=Article_Recirculation_Pos9 |title=Red Sox get back into game action and beat Northeastern |first=Peter |last=Abraham |newspaper=[[The Boston Globe]] |url-access=limited |date=February 22, 2019 |accessdate=February 22, 2019}}</ref>\n* On February 23, [[Grapefruit League]] play started with an 8\u20135 win over the [[2019 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.espn.com/mlb/game?gameId=401078891 |title=Yankees vs. Red Sox - Game Summary |website=[[ESPN]] |date=February 23, 2019 |accessdate=February 24, 2019}}</ref>\n{{collapse bottom}}\n\n{{collapse top|title=March 2019}}\n\n===March 2019===\n* On March 2, the team announced that it had reached agreement with 17 players, including [[Andrew Benintendi]] and [[Rafael Devers]], for one-year deals, resulting in all players on the major league roster being under contract for the season.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=RedSox |number=1101876043131031555 |title=The #RedSox today announced that the club has agreed to terms with 17 players on one-year contracts for the 2019 season |date=March 2, 2019 |accessdate=March 2, 2019}}</ref>\n* On March 6, MLB suspended RHP [[Steven Wright (baseball)|Steven Wright]] for 80 games, due to a positive test for a [[performance-enhancing substance]], Growth Hormone Releasing Peptide 2 ([[Pralmorelin|GHRP-2]]).<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.boston.com/sports/boston-red-sox/2019/03/06/steven-wright-suspended |title=Red Sox pitcher Steven Wright suspended for 80 games by MLB |first=Andrew |last=Mahoney |website=[[Boston.com]] |date=March 6, 2019 |accessdate=March 6, 2019}}</ref>\n* On March 17, manager [[Alex Cora]] named [[Chris Sale]] as the starting pitcher for [[Opening Day]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.masslive.com/sports/2019/03/chris-sale-to-start-for-boston-red-sox-opening-day-for-second-straight-year-on-schedule-to-pitch-fenway-park-opener.html |title=Chris Sale named Boston Red Sox 2019 Opening Day starter, on schedule to pitch Fenway Park opener |first=Christopher |last=Smith |website=masslive.com |date=March 17, 2019 |accessdate=March 17, 2019}}</ref>\n* On March 18, Cora announced that second baseman [[Dustin Pedroia]] would begin the season on the [[injured list]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.masslive.com/redsox/2019/03/boston-red-sox-2019-opening-day-roster-projection-dustin-pedroia-headed-to-injured-list-will-darwinzon-hernandez-take-his-spot.html |title=Boston Red Sox 2019 Opening Day roster projection: Dustin Pedroia headed to injured list, will Darwinzon Hernandez take his spot? |first=Christopher |last=Smith |website=masslive.com |date=March 19, 2019 |accessdate=March 19, 2019}}</ref>\n* On March 23, the Red Sox completed their spring training games in Florida with a record of 12\u201315.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mlb.com/standings/spring-training |title=Standings, Spring Training |website=[[MLB.com]] |accessdate=March 24, 2019}}</ref>\n* On March 25 and 26, Boston played their final two spring training games in [[Mesa, Arizona]], against the [[2019 Chicago Cubs season|Chicago Cubs]]. The Cubs won both games, by scores of 3\u20132 and 16\u20137.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mlb.com/redsox/schedule/2019-03 |title=Boston Red Sox Schedule |website=[[MLB.com]] |date=March 2019 |accessdate=March 26, 2019}}</ref>\n* On March 26, the Red Sox sent catcher [[Sandy Le\u00f3n]] outright to Triple-A Pawtucket.<ref name=MarchTrans/>\n* On March 27, the team placed [[Dustin Pedroia]], [[Steve Pearce (baseball)|Steve Pearce]], and [[Marco Hern\u00e1ndez]] on the 10-day [[injured list]],<ref name=MarchTrans>{{cite web |url=http://m.redsox.mlb.com/roster/transactions/2019/03 |title=Transactions |date=March 2019 |website=[[MLB.com]] |accessdate=March 27, 2019}}</ref> bringing the team's active roster size to 25, the MLB regular season limit.\n{{collapse bottom}}\n\n==Regular season==\nKey dates:<ref name=MLB19>{{cite news |url=https://www.mlb.com/redsox/news/2019-mlb-schedule-highlights/c-291189904 |title=The '19 schedule is out. Here are the highlights |first1=Manny |last1=Randhawa |first2=Chad |last2=Thornburg |website=[[MLB.com]] |date=August 22, 2018 |accessdate=October 31, 2018}}</ref>\n* March 28: season opener at [[Seattle Mariners]]\n* April 9: home opener vs. [[Toronto Blue Jays]]\n* June 29\u201330: [[2019 MLB London Series]] in [[England]] vs. [[New York Yankees]]\n* July 8\u201311: All-Star break\n** July 9: [[2019 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star Game]] at [[Progressive Field]] in [[Cleveland]]\n* July 12\u201314: home series vs. [[Los Angeles Dodgers]], whom Boston defeated in the [[2018 World Series]]\n* September 29: final regular season game, vs. [[Baltimore Orioles]] at Fenway Park\n\n===Opening Day, March 28 at [[2019 Seattle Mariners season|Seattle Mariners]]===\nThe 2019 regular season began on March 28 against the [[Seattle Mariners]] at [[T-Mobile Park]] (formerly known as Safeco Field). Manager [[Alex Cora]] named [[Chris Sale]] as Boston's [[Opening Day]] starting pitcher, and advised the starting lineup to the media on March 27.<ref name=CoraOpeningLineup/> Seattle scored seven runs off of Sale, who only pitched three innings and took the loss. Mariners' shortstop [[Tim Beckham]] had two home runs en route to a 12\u20134 final score. [[Mookie Betts]] went 3-for-5 at the plate.\n\n====Opening Day lineup====\n[[File:Chris Sale in 2017 (37185846582) (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|Opening Day starter Chris Sale]]\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! Order || No. || Player || Pos.\n|-\n| 1 || 16 || [[Andrew Benintendi]] || LF\n|-\n| 2 || 50 || [[Mookie Betts]] || RF\n|-\n| 3 || 11 || [[Rafael Devers]] || 3B\n|-\n| 4 || 28 || [[J. D. Martinez]] || DH\n|-\n| 5 || &nbsp;2 || [[Xander Bogaerts]] || SS\n|-\n| 6 || 18 || [[Mitch Moreland]] || 1B\n|-\n| 7 || 36 || [[Eduardo N\u00fa\u00f1ez]] || 2B\n|-\n| 8 || 19 || [[Jackie Bradley Jr.]] || CF\n|-\n| 9 || &nbsp;7 || [[Christian V\u00e1zquez]] || C\n|-\n| \u2013 ||41 || [[Chris Sale]] || P\n|}\n\n{{collapse top|title=March/April}}\n\n===March===\n'''March 28\u2013March 31, at [[2019 Seattle Mariners season|Seattle Mariners]]'''<br>\nAfter a 12\u20134 loss in the season opener, the Red Sox came from behind to win the second game of the season, 7\u20136. [[Brian Johnson (pitcher)|Brian Johnson]] got the win in relief, with [[Matt Barnes (baseball)|Matt Barnes]] picking up the team's first [[save (baseball)|save]] of the season. [[Mitch Moreland]]'s three-run home run in the ninth inning provided the winning margin. A late Boston rally in the third game of the series came up a run short, as Seattle held on for a 6\u20135 win. Boston again rallied late in the fourth game, loading the bases with one out in the ninth, but fell two runs short, losing 10\u20138. During the series, only one Red Sox starting pitcher, [[Nathan Eovaldi]] in the second game, lasted five innings.\n\n<small>'''Red Sox lost the series 1\u20133 (24\u201334 runs)'''</small>\n\n===April===\n'''April 1\u2013April 4, at [[2019 Oakland Athletics season|Oakland Athletics]]'''<br>\nThe Red Sox were held scoreless in the first two games of the series, falling to the Athletics by scores of 7\u20130 and 1\u20130. It was Boston's first time being shutout back-to-back since their [[2015 Boston Red Sox season|2015 season]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bostonherald.com/2019/04/03/chris-sales-velocity-concerning-in-red-sox-shutout-loss-to-as/ |title=Chris Sale\u2019s velocity, Red Sox offense concerning in another shutout loss |first=Jason |last=Mastrodonato |website=[[Boston Herald]] |date=April 3, 2019 |accessdate=April 3, 2019}}</ref> Each game featured an outfield assist by Oakland center fielder [[Ram\u00f3n Laureano]] to retire [[Xander Bogaerts]]; at home in the first game, and at third base in the second game.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.masslive.com/redsox/2019/04/boston-red-soxs-xander-bogaerts-thrown-out-at-third-base-in-ninth-inning-of-1-0-game-vs-athletics-video.html |title=Ramon Laureano throw: Boston Red Sox\u2019s Xander Bogaerts gunned down at third base in ninth inning of 1-0 loss to Athletics (video) |first=Chris |last=Cotillo |website=masslive.com |date=April 3, 2019 |accessdate=April 3, 2019}}</ref> The Red Sox ended their four-game losing streak with a 6\u20133 win in the third game of the series. [[Blake Swihart]] was 3-for-4 at the plate including a home run, while [[Ryan Brasier]] recorded his first major league [[save (baseball)|save]].<ref>{{cite tweet |user=IanMBrowne |number=1113675161046212613 |title=That was Ryan Brasier's first career save |date=April 4, 2019 |accessdate=April 4, 2019}}</ref> In the final game of the series, [[J. D. Martinez]] hit his third home run of the season, but the Red Sox were unable to win consecutive games, losing 7\u20133. Boston's 2\u20136 start was the worst for a defending [[World Series]] champion since the [[1998 Florida Marlins season|1998 Florida Marlins]],<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/nationals/betts-grounder-hits-3b-bag-bosox-end-4-game-skid-beat-as/2019/04/04/04b76b30-569e-11e9-aa83-504f086bf5d6_story.html |title=Laureano nails another Red Sox runner, Athletics win 7-3 |first=Gideon |last=Rubin |agency=[[Associated Press|AP]] |website=[[The Washington Post]] |date=April 4, 2019 |accessdate=April 4, 2019}}</ref> who were 1\u20137 through eight games played.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/teams/FLA/1998-schedule-scores.shtml |title=1998 Florida Marlins Schedule |website=[[Baseball-Reference.com]] |accessdate=April 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\n<small>'''Red Sox lost the series 1\u20133 (9\u201318 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''April 5\u2013April 7, at [[2019 Arizona Diamondbacks season|Arizona Diamondbacks]]'''<br>\nBoston fell to Arizona in the Diamondbacks' home opener, 15\u20138, after falling behind 14\u20131 through six innings. Starter [[Rick Porcello]] allowed 10 hits and seven runs in {{frac|4|2|3}} innings, followed by [[Brian Johnson (pitcher)|Brian Johnson]] who allowed six hits and seven runs in {{frac|1|1|3}} innings. Late in the game, both [[Mookie Betts]] and [[Mitch Moreland]] homered, while infielder [[Eduardo N\u00fa\u00f1ez]] pitched an inning in relief. The second game of the series was tied in the bottom of the ninth, when Betts threw out [[Eduardo Escobar]] at the plate as he attempted to score from second on a single to right. However, a two-out [[wikt:walk-off|walk-off]] single by the next batter, catcher [[Carson Kelly]], gave the Diamondbacks a 5\u20134 win. Starting pitcher [[David Price (baseball)|David Price]] allowed four runs in six innings for a [[no decision]], while going 1-for-2 at the plate with an RBI. The team's record through 10 games was their worst start since [[2011 Boston Red Sox season|2011]], which also began 2\u20138.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bostonherald.com/2019/04/06/red-sox-fall-to-diamondbacks-5-4-on-walkoff-loss/ |title=Red Sox fall to Diamondbacks, 5-4, on walkoff loss |first=Jason |last=Mastrodonato |website=[[Boston Herald]] |date=April 7, 2019 |accessdate=April 7, 2019}}</ref> The Red Sox won the final game of the series, 1\u20130, with the only run coming on a Moreland home run. Five Boston pitchers combined to shutout the Diamondbacks. Two Boston relief pitchers ([[Marcus Walden]] and [[Matt Barnes (baseball)|Matt Barnes]]) batted, the first time that had occurred since 1972.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=SoxNotes |number=1115013268551159808 |title=This is the first time in the DH era that multiple Red Sox relief pitchers have had a plate appearance in the same game |date=April 7, 2019 |accessdate=April 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n<small>'''Red Sox lost the series 1\u20132 (13\u201320 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''April 9 & April 11, vs. [[2019 Toronto Blue Jays season|Toronto Blue Jays]]'''<br>\n[[File:Dustin Pedroia at the bat.jpg|thumb|right|upright|[[Dustin Pedroia]] made his 2019 debut with the Red Sox on April 9.]]\nPrior to the home opener, the Red Sox celebrated their [[2018 World Series]] victory, including raising a World Series banner and awarding [[World Series ring]]s.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.boston.com/sports/boston-red-sox/2019/04/09/red-sox-ring-ceremony-opening-day-patriots |title=The Patriots joined the Red Sox to celebrate both teams\u2019 recent championships |first=Hayden |last=Bird |website=[[Boston.com]] |date=April 9, 2019 |accessdate=April 9, 2019}}</ref> In the game, Boston jumped out to an early 2\u20130 lead after two innings, only to fall behind 5\u20132 at the end of four, en route to a 7\u20135 defeat. [[Chris Sale]] gave up five runs in four innings for the loss, including a steal of home by [[Lourdes Gurriel Jr.]] For the Red Sox, [[Mookie Betts]] and [[Mitch Moreland]] both homered, while [[Dustin Pedroia]] was 1-for-4 in his first MLB game since May 2018. In the second game of this short series, Toronto led 5\u20133 after three innings and 6\u20135 after eight. In the ninth inning, a Betts walk followed by a Moreland double tied the game. Two subsequent walks (one intentional) loaded the bases, then [[Rafael Devers]] delivered a [[wikt:walk-off|walk-off]] single, giving Boston a 7\u20136 win.\n\n<small>'''Red Sox tied the series 1\u20131 (12\u201313 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''April 12\u2013April 15, vs. [[2019 Baltimore Orioles season|Baltimore Orioles]]'''<br>\nThe opening game of the series was a 6\u20134 win for Boston, giving the team their first back-to-back wins of the season. [[Xander Bogaerts]] was 3-for-4 at the plate, while [[Andrew Benintendi]] hit his first home run of the year. [[Eduardo Rodr\u00edguez (left-handed pitcher)|Eduardo Rodr\u00edguez]] was the first Red Sox starting pitcher to record a win this season, while [[Ryan Brasier]] notched his third save. In the second game of the series, Red Sox starter [[Rick Porcello]] took the loss to fall to 0\u20133 on the season, as the Orioles won, 9\u20135. [[Christian V\u00e1zquez]] was the only Boston player with two hits, one of them a home run. Baltimore first baseman [[Chris Davis (baseball)|Chris Davis]] ended his streak of 54 consecutive [[at bat]]s without a hit,<ref>{{cite news |last=Townsend |first=Mark |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/news/chris-davis-snaps-mlb-record-54-atbat-hitless-streak-172753604.html |title=Chris Davis snaps MLB record 54 at-bat hitless streak with clutch single |website=[[Yahoo Sports]] |date=April 13, 2019 |accessdate=April 13, 2019}}</ref> going 3-for-5 with four RBIs. The third game of the series saw [[David Price (baseball)|David Price]] hold the Orioles to three hits and no runs through seven innings, as the Red Sox won, 4\u20130. Benintendi had to leave the game shortly after fouling a pitch off of his right foot in the bottom of the third inning,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.boston.com/sports/boston-red-sox/2019/04/14/andrew-benintendi-leaves-sundays-game-after-fouling-ball-off-foot |title=Andrew Benintendi leaves Sunday\u2019s game after fouling ball off foot |agency=[[Associated Press|AP]] |website=[[Boston.com]] |date=April 14, 2019 |accessdate=April 14, 2019}}</ref> while Bogaerts had three RBIs on an eighth inning home run. The closing game of the series was an 8\u20131 Orioles win on the day of the [[Boston Marathon]], with the Red Sox using a total of six pitchers.\n\n<small>'''Red Sox tied the series 2\u20132 (16\u201321 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''April 16\u2013April 17, at [[2019 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]]'''<br>\nThe first game of the season between the [[Yankees\u2013Red Sox rivalry|longtime rivals]] was an 8\u20130 shutout by the Yankees, as [[Chris Sale]] took the loss to fall to 0\u20134 on the season. Boston's record fell to 6\u201312, the team's worst start since the [[1996 Boston Red Sox season|1996 Red Sox]] started 3\u201315.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=IanMBrowne |number=1118319033437380608 |title=Red Sox lose, 8-0 |date=April 16, 2019 |accessdate=April 16, 2019}}</ref> In the second game of this two-game series, Boston starter [[Nathan Eovaldi]] held New York to three hits and one run through six innings, with the Red Sox leading, 3\u20131. However, after the Yankees loaded the bases in the bottom of the seventh inning off of Red Sox reliever [[Brandon Workman]], [[Brett Gardner]] hit a [[Grand slam (baseball)|grand slam]] off of [[Ryan Brasier]], giving New York a 5\u20133 lead and ultimately the win by that score. [[J. D. Martinez]] and [[Christian V\u00e1zquez]] homered for Boston, while [[Dustin Pedroia]] left the game in the middle of the second inning due to left knee discomfort.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/sports/redsox/2019/04/17/shaughnessy/fyKkICXvfXdFcIIUqImn9I/story.html |title=Is this the end for Dustin Pedroia? |first=Dan |last=Shaughnessy |website=[[The Boston Globe]] |url-access=limited |date=April 17, 2019 |accessdate=April 17, 2019}}</ref> Boston's record of 6\u201313 was the worst for a defending World Series champion through 19 games since the [[1998 Florida Marlins season|1998 Florida Marlins]] started 5\u201314.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.boston.com/sports/boston-red-sox/2019/04/17/gardner-slam-lifts-yanks-over-red-sox-5-3-for-2-game-sweep |title=Gardner slam lifts Yanks over Red Sox 5-3 for 2-game sweep |first=Ronald |last=Blum |agency=[[Associated Press|AP]] |website=[[Boston.com]] |date=April 17, 2019 |accessdate=April 17, 2019}}</ref> Boston's [[run differential]] of -42 set a new MLB-worst for a defending champion through 19 games, surpassing the -37 of the [[1988 Minnesota Twins season|1988 Minnesota Twins]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.espn.com/mlb/story/_/id/26549821/for-scuffling-red-sox-getting-late-early |title=For scuffling Red Sox, it's getting late early |first=Joon |last=Lee |website=[[ESPN]] |date=April 18, 2019 |accessdate=April 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\n<small>'''Red Sox lost the series 0\u20132 (3\u201313 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''April 19\u2013April 21, at [[2019 Tampa Bay Rays season|Tampa Bay Rays]]'''<br>\n[[File:Ryan David Brasier.jpg|thumb|right|upright|[[Ryan Brasier]] earned a [[Save (baseball)|save]] in each game of the April 19\u201321 series.]]\nThe opening game against the [[American League East|AL East]] leading Rays was a 6\u20134 Red Sox win. Tied 4\u20134 in the eighth inning, [[Mookie Betts]] and [[Mitch Moreland]] hit back-to-back home runs, and [[Ryan Brasier]] pitched a scoreless ninth inning for his fourth [[Save (baseball)|save]] of the season. In the second game of the series, the Red Sox jumped out to an early 5\u20130 lead, with four runs coming on a [[Grand slam (baseball)|grand slam]] by [[Andrew Benintendi]] in the second inning. The Rays came back to tie the game, 5\u20135, through eight innings. Boston scored one run in the top of the ninth, helped in part by a [[pinch hitter|pinch hit]] double by [[Michael Chavis]] in his first MLB [[at bat]]. Brasier closed out the game for his fifth save of the season, the final out coming when catcher [[Christian V\u00e1zquez]] threw to first base to [[pickoff]] Rays outfielder [[Tommy Pham]]. The final game of the series was Boston's first [[extra innings]] game of the season. The Red Sox had a 3\u20132 lead after seven innings, but the Rays tied it in the bottom of the eighth. After scoreless ninth and tenth innings, Boston scored in the top of the eleventh, on a [[sacrifice fly]] by V\u00e1zquez that scored [[Rafael Devers]]. Brasier then got his third save in three days, closing out the 4\u20133 win.\n\n<small>'''Red Sox won the series 3\u20130 (16\u201312 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''April 22\u2013April 25, vs. [[2019 Detroit Tigers season|Detroit Tigers]]'''<br>\nThe April 22 game was postponed due to rain, resulting in a day-night [[Doubleheader (baseball)|doubleheader]] being scheduled for April 23.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.masslive.com/redsox/2019/04/boston-red-sox-game-postponed-due-to-rain-tigers-red-sox-doubleheader-at-fenway-park-on-tuesday.html |title=Boston Red Sox game postponed due to rain Monday, doubleheader vs. Tigers at Fenway Park on Tuesday |first=Christopher |last=Smith |website=masslive.com |date=April 22, 2019 |accessdate=April 22, 2019}}</ref> In the first game of a Tuesday doubleheader, the teams played to a 3\u20133 tie through seven innings, before the Tigers scored three runs off of [[Colten Brewer]] en route to a 7\u20134 win, ending the Red Sox' winning streak at three games. [[Xander Bogaerts]] had two home runs, as Boston was held to five hits total. In the second game of the doubleheader, the Tigers went ahead 3\u20130 in the fourth inning. Boston closed the lead to 3\u20132 entering the ninth, but Detroit got an insurance run before [[Closer (baseball)|closer]] [[Shane Greene]] notched his 11th [[Save (baseball)|save]] of the season in the 4\u20132 Tigers' win. The Red Sox got a total of five innings of one-run relief from [[Darwinzon Hern\u00e1ndez]] and [[Travis Lakins]], both of whom made their MLB debuts. In the third game of the series, Boston held a 4\u20131 lead after six innings, then scored seven runs in the bottom of the eighth, en route to an 11\u20134 win. [[J. D. Martinez]] was 3-for-4 at the plate, while [[Eduardo Rodr\u00edguez (left-handed pitcher)|Eduardo Rodr\u00edguez]] held Detroit to one run in six innings and got the win. The series' final game was a 7\u20133 Boston win, with [[Rick Porcello]] getting his first win of the season, and [[Michael Chavis]] hitting his second MLB home run.\n\n<small>'''Red Sox tied the series 2\u20132 (24\u201318 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''April 26\u2013April 28, vs. [[2019 Tampa Bay Rays season|Tampa Bay Rays]]'''\n\nThe April 26 game was postponed due to rain, resulting in a day-night [[Doubleheader (baseball)|doubleheader]] being scheduled for June 8.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.boston.com/sports/boston-red-sox/2019/04/26/red-sox-rays-postponed-doubleheader |title=Red Sox, Rays washed out in series opener |first=Gethin |last=Coolbaugh |website=[[Boston.com]] |date=April 26, 2019 |accessdate=April 26, 2019}}</ref> In Saturday's game, Tampa Bay starter [[Charlie Morton (pitcher)|Charlie Morton]] held Boston to two hits and no runs through six innings, as the Rays went on to a 2\u20131 win. An eighth inning homer by [[Mookie Betts]] was the Red Sox' only run. In Sunday's game, Red Sox starter [[Chris Sale]] allowed two runs in each of the first two innings (two of the four runs were unearned), taking the loss in a 5\u20132 Rays win. [[Michael Chavis]] hit his third MLB home run.\n\n<small>'''Red Sox lost the series 0\u20132 (3\u20137 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''April 29\u2013April 30, vs. [[2019 Oakland Athletics season|Oakland Athletics]]'''\n\nIn the first game of a three-game series, Boston fell behind 4\u20130 after two innings, then rallied for six runs in the bottom of the third, en route to a 9\u20134 win. [[Mookie Betts]] was 3-for-4, while [[Michael Chavis]] had three RBIs. [[Ryan Brasier]] got the win in a seven-pitcher effort from the Boston staff. The second game of the series was a 5\u20131 Boston win, as starter [[Rick Porcello]] pitched eight scoreless innings for the win. [[Mookie Betts]] and [[Mitch Moreland]] each homered.\n{{collapse bottom}}\n\n{{collapse top|title=May}}\n\n===May===\n'''May 1, vs. [[2019 Oakland Athletics season|Oakland Athletics]] (cont'd)'''<br>\nIn the third and final game of the series, Boston starting pitcher [[H\u00e9ctor Vel\u00e1zquez (baseball)|H\u00e9ctor Vel\u00e1zquez]] was removed after 43 pitches in two innings. The [[bullpen]] provided six runs of scoreless relief, as Boston built a 7\u20131 lead en route to a 7\u20133 win and series sweep. [[Mitch Moreland]] and [[Christian V\u00e1zquez]] each homered.\n\n<small>'''Red Sox won the series 3\u20130 (21\u20138 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''May 2\u2013May 5, at [[2019 Chicago White Sox season|Chicago White Sox]]'''\n\nIn the first game of a four-game series, the Red Sox took a 4\u20133 lead into the bottom of the ninth. A one-out error by third baseman [[Rafael Devers]] put a runner on first. A single then put runners at the corners, and [[Nicky Delmonico]] followed with a three-run [[walk-off home run]] off of [[Ryan Brasier]], giving Chicago the win, 6\u20134. [[Chris Sale]] got his first win of the season in the second game of the series, a 6\u20131 Boston win, allowing no runs and three hits in six innings pitched. Devers and [[Michael Chavis]] each homered. The third game of the series was notable for the Red Sox scoring nine runs with two outs in the third inning; after the first two batters were retired, Boston had 10 hits in a row (four singles, three doubles, and three home runs).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/mlb/playbyplay?gameId=401075215 |title=Red Sox vs. White Sox - Play-By-Play |website=[[ESPN]] |date=May 4, 2019 |accessdate=May 4, 2019}}</ref> Chavis and [[Christian V\u00e1zquez]] each had four hits during the game, a 15\u20132 Boston win. The series' closing game was tied, 2\u20132, going into the eighth inning, when Boston scored seven runs. Four runs came on a [[Grand slam (baseball)|grand slam]] by [[Xander Bogaerts]], as the Red Sox won, 9\u20132.\n\n<small>'''Red Sox won the series 3\u20131 (34\u201311 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''May 6\u2013May 8, at [[2019 Baltimore Orioles season|Baltimore Orioles]]'''<br>\n[[File:Heath Hembree.jpg|thumb|right|upright|[[Heath Hembree]] got his first MLB [[Save (baseball)|save]] on May 8.]]\nThe opening game of the series saw all of Baltimore's runs come on a [[Grand slam (baseball)|grand slam]] by [[Jonathan Villar]] off of [[Josh Smith (right-handed pitcher)|Josh Smith]], who was making a spot start for Boston. The Red Sox plated only a single run, resulting in a 4\u20131 loss. The first five batters in Boston's order were a collective 0-for-19. With [[David Price (baseball)|David Price]] on the [[injured list]], [[H\u00e9ctor Vel\u00e1zquez (baseball)|H\u00e9ctor Vel\u00e1zquez]] started the second game of the series, leaving after three innings with the score tied, 2\u20132. [[Marcus Walden]] then pitched three innings in relief, later getting credit for the win, as Boston led 6\u20133 after six innings. [[Matt Barnes (baseball)|Matt Barnes]] closed out the 8\u20135 win with a four-out [[Save (baseball)|save]]. [[J. D. Martinez]] hit his 200th MLB career home run;<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/sports/redsox/2019/05/07/martinez-hits-career-home-run/cY8JfYosfeo7ZdYeQwClbP/story.html |title=J.D. Martinez hits 200th career home run |first=Alex |last=Speier |website=[[The Boston Globe]] |date=May 7, 2019 |accessdate=May 7, 2019}}</ref> [[Xander Bogaerts]] and [[Mitch Moreland]] also homered. The final game of the series featured [[Chris Sale]] holding the Orioles to three hits and one run through eight innings, including pitching an [[immaculate inning]] in the bottom of the seventh.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://boston.cbslocal.com/2019/05/08/chris-sale-throws-immaculate-inning-9-pitches-all-strikes-vs-orioles/ |title=Chris Sale Throws Immaculate Inning \u2014 9 Pitches, All Strikes \u2014 Vs. Orioles |website=[[WBZ-TV]] |date=May 8, 2019 |accessdate=May 9, 2019}}</ref> Sale received a [[no decision]], as the game went to [[extra innings]], tied 1\u20131. There were no runs scored in the first two extra frames, with [[Jackie Bradley Jr.]] reaching over the outfield wall to prevent a game-winning homer by [[Trey Mancini]] in the bottom of the 11th.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.masslive.com/redsox/2019/05/jackie-bradley-jrs-catch-saves-walk-off-homer-for-boston-red-sox-video.html |title=Jackie Bradley Jr.\u2019s catch saves walk-off homer for Boston Red Sox (video) |first=Chris |last=Cotillo |website=masslive.com |date=May 8, 2019 |accessdate=May 9, 2019}}</ref> [[Andrew Benintendi]] hit a solo home run to give Boston a 2\u20131 lead in the top of the 12th, and [[Heath Hembree]] closed out the win with his first MLB save. The win gave the Red Sox a 19\u201319 record, the first time the team was at .500 since the second game of the season.\n\n<small>'''Red Sox won the series 2\u20131 (11\u201310 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''May 10\u2013May 12, vs. [[2019 Seattle Mariners season|Seattle Mariners]]'''\n\n[[Eduardo Rodr\u00edguez (left-handed pitcher)|Eduardo Rodr\u00edguez]] started the first game of the series, holding Seattle scoreless through seven innings. Boston's offense had 15 hits, winning by a 14\u20131 score. [[Andrew Benintendi]], [[Rafael Devers]], and [[Mitch Moreland]] each homered. With the win, the Red Sox reached 20\u201319, their first winning record of the season.  In the second game of the series, Seattle jumped out to an early 4\u20130 lead in the top of the first inning; Boston responded with one run in bottom of the second and eight runs in the bottom of the third. Boston's 9\u20135 victory gave the team their first four-game winning streak of the season. [[Rick Porcello]] went {{frac|6|2|3}} innings and got the win. Every Boston batter [[base on balls|walk]]ed at least once, while Moreland and [[Sandy Le\u00f3n]] each homered. The final game of the series was an 11\u20132 Boston win, with [[Michael Chavis]] going 3-for-5 at the plate with five RBIs, while [[J. D. Martinez]] had two home runs.\n\n<small>'''Red Sox won the series 3\u20130 (34\u20138 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''May 14\u2013May 15, vs. [[2019 Colorado Rockies season|Colorado Rockies]]'''\n\nIn the opener of a two-game series, [[Chris Sale]] struck out 17 batters, a new career high.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=alexspeier |number=1128467670335131648 |title=Career-high 17 Ks for Sale |date=May 14, 2019 |accessdate=May 14, 2019}}</ref> He left the game after seven innings with a 3\u20132 lead, but received a [[no decision]] as the game went to [[extra innings]], tied 4\u20134. Colorado scored a run in the 11th inning off of two walks and a single for a 5\u20134 win, ending Boston's winning streak at five games. Boston's relievers had seven more strikeouts; the total of 24 tied the single-game record for the Red Sox franchise.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=SoxNotes |number=1128484857628303360 |title=Red Sox pitchers have tied the franchise record for most strikeouts in a game (24). |date=May 14, 2019 |accessdate=May 14, 2019}}</ref> The second game of the series also went to extra innings; after Boston built an early 5\u20130 lead, Colorado tied the game at five in the seventh inning. In the 10th inning, the Rockies had a leadoff double, but were unable to score. In Boston's half of the inning, [[Xander Bogaerts]] doubled, [[Rafael Devers]] was intentionally walked, and then [[Michael Chavis]] drove in Bogaerts to give the Red Sox the win, 6\u20135.\n\n<small>'''Red Sox tied the series 1\u20131 (10\u201310 runs)'''</small>\n\n[[File:Brandon Workman on September 28, 2013.jpg|thumb|right|upright|[[Brandon Workman]] recorded his first MLB [[Save (baseball)|save]] on May 19.]]\n'''May 17\u2013May 19, vs. [[2019 Houston Astros season|Houston Astros]]'''\n\nBoston lost the first game of a three-game series, 3\u20131. A two-run homer by [[George Springer]] in the eighth inning took the Astros from a 1\u20130 deficit to a 2\u20131 lead. [[Xander Bogaerts]] and [[Christian V\u00e1zquez]] each had three hits for the Red Sox. Houston scored five runs in the second game of the series before Boston had a chance to bat, chasing starter [[H\u00e9ctor Vel\u00e1zquez (baseball)|H\u00e9ctor Vel\u00e1zquez]] after {{frac|1|3}} of an inning. Boston got no closer than trailing by three runs, 6\u20133, after the fourth inning, as the Astros went on to win, 7\u20133. V\u00e1zquez homered for the Red Sox. In the final game of the series, Houston had a 3\u20131 lead after three innings. In the fifth inning, Boston tied the game, 3\u20133, on a [[Michael Chavis]] solo home run, followed by a [[Mookie Betts]] double and Bogaerts RBI single. Bogaerts again drove in Betts in the seventh inning, giving the Red Sox what proved to be the winning run in a 4\u20133 victory. [[Brandon Workman]] got the [[Save (baseball)|save]], the first of his MLB career.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=RedSox |number=1130220822101221381 |title=Brandon Workman records his first career save! |date=May 19, 2019 |accessdate=May 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\n<small>'''Red Sox lost the series 1\u20132 (8\u201313 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''May 20\u2013May 23, at [[2019 Toronto Blue Jays season|Toronto Blue Jays]]'''\n\nThe Red Sox won the first game of the series, 12\u20132, while out-hitting the Blue Jays, 16 to 3. [[Michael Chavis]], [[Jackie Bradley Jr.]], [[Xander Bogaerts]], and [[Rafael Devers]] all homered. Boston lost the second game of the series, 10\u20133, after Toronto jumped out to a 6\u20130 lead through five innings, powered by [[Designated hitter|DH]] [[Rowdy Tellez]] with two home runs for five RBIs. Boston's runs came on three solo homers; by Bradley Jr., Devers, and [[Mitch Moreland]]. The third game of the series was a 6\u20135 Boston win in 13 innings. Toronto erased one-run deficits both in the bottom of the ninth and in the bottom of the 12th. Boston's winning run came on a Chavis homer; Devers and [[Mookie Betts]] also homered earlier in the game. In the final game of the series, Toronto scored first and last, however it was a Boston win, 8\u20132. [[Ryan Weber]] held the Blue Jays to one run on three hits in six innings, earning his first MLB win as a starting pitcher.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.espn.com/mlb/recap?gameId=401075473 |title=Red Sox vs. Blue Jays - Game Recap |agency=[[Associated Press]] |website=[[ESPN]] |date=May 23, 2019 |accessdate=May 23, 2019}}</ref> [[Steve Pearce (baseball)|Steve Pearce]] hit his first home run of the season.\n\n<small>'''Red Sox won the series 3\u20131 (29\u201319 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''May 24\u2013May 26, at [[2019 Houston Astros season|Houston Astros]]'''\n\nBoston out-hit Houston, 7\u20134, in the first game of the series, but lost, 4\u20133. [[Chris Sale]] allowed four runs (two earned) in six innings and took the loss, falling to 1\u20136 on the season. Houston had a 4\u20130 lead through four innings, with Boston scoring on solo home runs by [[Xander Bogaerts]], [[Jackie Bradley Jr.]], and [[Christian V\u00e1zquez]] in the sixth, eighth, and ninth innings, respectively. In the second game of the series, Red Sox starter [[David Price (baseball)|David Price]] left in the first inning, due to [[Influenza-like illness|flu-like symptoms]].<ref>{{cite tweet |user=Ken_Rosenthal |number=1132440709766701058 |title=David Price sent word to me that his arm/elbow is fine. |date=May 25, 2019 |accessdate=May 25, 2019}}</ref> The game remained scoreless until Houston took a 2\u20130 lead in the sixth inning. Boston rallied to tied the game in the top of the ninth, 3\u20133, but was unable to take the lead, despite having runners on first and third with no outs. In the bottom of the ninth, the Astros had a double, two walks, and a game-winning single by [[Carlos Correa]], giving the Red Sox another 4\u20133 loss. Houston took a 1\u20130 first-inning lead in the final game of the series, however Boston scored four unanswered runs to win, 4\u20131. [[Rafael Devers]] hit his seventh home run of the season and [[Marcus Walden]] got the [[Save (baseball)|save]].\n\n<small>'''Red Sox lost the series 1\u20132 (10\u20139 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''May 27\u2013May 29, vs. [[2019 Cleveland Indians season|Cleveland Indians]]'''\n\nCleveland took an early 3\u20130 lead in the first game of the series, with Boston evening the score, 3\u20133, at the end of four innings. Boston then scored six runs in the fifth, and went on to win, 12\u20135. [[Sandy Le\u00f3n]] had a three-run homer and [[J. D. Martinez]] hit two home runs. The second game of the series had a 69-minute rain delay during the second inning. Scoreless until the sixth inning, Boston took a 3\u20130 lead, and held a 5\u20132 lead going into the ninth inning. Cleveland rallied for five runs in the ninth, with the tying runs being charged to [[Ryan Brasier]], and [[Travis Lakins]] taking the loss as Boston fell, 7\u20135. The final game of the series featured 23 runs and 32 hits, with Cleveland winning, 14\u20139. Four different Red Sox homered, including [[Andrew Benintendi]], who had three RBIs.\n\n<small>'''Red Sox lost the series 1\u20132 (26\u201326 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''May 30\u2013May 31, at [[2019 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]]'''<br>\nThe first game of the series was postponed due to rain and rescheduled for August 3 at 7 p.m.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=RedSox |number=1134202458052464650 |title=It looks like we\u2019re not playing baseball in the Bronx tonight... The game will be made up on August 3rd at 7pm. |date=May 30, 2019 |accessdate=May 30, 2019}}</ref> In Friday's game, Boston took an early lead on a second-inning [[Rafael Devers]] solo home run, but New York scored four unanswered runs to win, 4\u20131, giving the Red Sox their fifth defeat in seven games. [[Chris Sale]] took the loss and fell to 1\u20137 for the season, as Boston (29\u201328) ended the month {{frac|8|1|2}} [[games behind]] the division-leading Yankees (37\u201319).\n{{collapse bottom}}\n\n{{collapse top|title=June}}\n\n===June===\n'''June 1\u2013June 2, at [[2019 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]] (cont'd)'''<br>\nBoston scored first in Saturday's game, with New York taking a 3\u20131 lead at the end of the second inning. The Red Sox tied the game in the fourth inning, on a solo home run by [[Xander Bogaerts]] and an RBI single by [[Sandy Le\u00f3n]]. A two-run homer by Yankees catcher [[Gary S\u00e1nchez]] in the fifth inning was the only other scoring of the game. New York's 5\u20133 victory put them {{frac|9|1|2}} [[games behind|games ahead]] of Boston, as the Red Sox fell back to .500 (29\u201329) for the season. In the final game of the series, Boston led the entire way, with New York drawing no closer than 3\u20132 at the end of the fourth inning, en route to an 8\u20135 Red Sox win. Bogaerts and [[J. D. Martinez]] both homered. Before the game, manager [[Alex Cora]] announced that [[Mookie Betts]] would be the team's [[leadoff hitter]] for the rest of the season, as he had been during 2018.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bostonherald.com/2019/06/01/cora-mookie-betts-to-lead-off-for-red-sox-for-rest-of-the-season/ |title=Cora: Mookie Betts to lead off for Red Sox for \u2018rest of the season\u2019 |first=Jason |last=Mastrodonato |website=[[Boston Herald]] |date=June 2, 2019 |accessdate=June 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\n<small>'''Red Sox lost the series 1\u20132 (12\u201314 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''June 4\u2013June 6, at [[2019 Kansas City Royals season|Kansas City Royals]]'''<br>\nAfter Kansas City had an early 2\u20130 lead in the opening game of the series, Boston went ahead by a run in the sixth. [[Eduardo N\u00fa\u00f1ez]] then hit a [[Pinch hitter|pinch hit]] three-run homer in the eighth inning, as Boston pulled away for an 8\u20133 win. The middle game of the series was a complete game shutout by [[Chris Sale]], who also pitched his second [[immaculate inning]] of the season.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=MLB |number=1136466377676591104 |title=For the second time this year, Chris Sale was immaculate. |date=June 5, 2019 |accessdate=June 5, 2019}}</ref> [[Rafael Devers]] hit his ninth home run of the season as Boston won, 8\u20130. Boston completed the sweep with a 7\u20135 win on Thursday afternoon, using seven pitchers with [[Colten Brewer]] getting the win. [[Mookie Betts]] hit his 10th home run of the season.\n[[File:Marco Hern\u00e1ndez on May 30, 2016.jpg|thumb|right|upright|On June 8, [[Marco Hern\u00e1ndez]] played in his first MLB game since May 2017.]]\n<small>'''Red Sox won the series 3\u20130 (23\u20138 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''June 7\u2013June 9, vs. [[2019 Tampa Bay Rays season|Tampa Bay Rays]]'''<br>\nThe Rays defeated the Red Sox, 5\u20131, in the opening game of the series, as Tampa Bay starter [[Yonny Chirinos]] did not allow a baserunner until the sixth inning. [[Xander Bogaerts]] had two of Boston's four hits, and the team's only RBI. In the first game of a Saturday [[Doubleheader (baseball)|doubleheader]], Tampa Bay had a 4\u20131 lead at the end of the second inning, and went on to win, 9\u20132. [[Marco Hern\u00e1ndez]] played in his first MLB game since the 2017 season, and [[Jackie Bradley Jr.]] hit his fifth home run of the season. The second game of the doubleheader was a 5\u20131 Red Sox win, as [[David Price (baseball)|David Price]] held the Rays to one run in six innings, with 10 strikeouts. The final game of the series was a 6\u20131 Rays win on Sunday, with Hern\u00e1ndez driving in Boston's only run.\n\n<small>'''Red Sox lost the series 1\u20133 (9\u201321 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''June 10\u2013June 13, vs. [[2019 Texas Rangers season|Texas Rangers]]'''<br>\n[[Chris Sale]] started the series' opener, holding Texas to one run ([[Earned run|unearned]]) on three hits in seven innings, while striking out 10. Boston held a 2\u20131 lead going into the ninth, however the Rangers rallied for two runs, going ahead 3\u20132. [[Brock Holt]] then had a two-out RBI in the bottom of the ninth to send the game to [[extra innings]]. Texas scored what proved to be the winning run in the top of the 11th, on a double and a single, for a 4\u20133 final. The second game of the series was a 9\u20135 Rangers win, dropping the Red Sox back to .500 on the season (34\u201334). The game included an [[inside-the-park home run]] by [[Hunter Pence]], ejections of both managers ([[Alex Cora]] for Boston, [[Chris Woodward]] for Texas), and the first career ejection of [[Andrew Benintendi]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.star-telegram.com/sports/mlb/texas-rangers/article231456758.html |title=Rangers beat Red Sox 9-5, but Hernandez\u2019s ejection of Woodward overshadows victory |first=Jeff |last=Wilson |website=[[Fort Worth Star-Telegram]] |location=[[Fort Worth, Texas]] |date=June 11, 2019 |accessdate=June 11, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet |user=ChrisCotillo |number=1138621817575432192 |title=First career ejection for the mild-mannered Andrew Benintendi. |date=June 11, 2019 |accessdate=June 11, 2019}}</ref> Texas took a 2\u20131 first-inning lead in the third game of the series, with Boston going ahead 3\u20132 in the fifth inning, and the Rangers tying the score at 3\u20133 in the top of the eighth. In the bottom of the ninth, the Red Sox loaded the bases on a double, and single, and a walk. [[Mookie Betts]] then also walked, forcing in [[Marco Hern\u00e1ndez]] with the winning run, 4\u20133. In the final game of the series, the Red Sox were down 6\u20131 in the middle of the second inning, with starter [[David Price (baseball)|David Price]] leaving the game after allowing six runs on five hits in {{frac|1|1|3}} innings. Boston then used seven relief pitchers, who did not allow any more runs. The offense tied the game in the fifth inning, and a home run by [[Xander Bogaerts]] (one of five the team hit) in the seventh inning put Boston ahead, 7\u20136. With a depleted bullpen and [[Heath Hembree]] not available, [[Josh Smith (right-handed pitcher)|Josh Smith]] closed out the victory for his first MLB [[Save (baseball)|save]].\n\n<small>'''Red Sox tied the series 2\u20132 (19\u201322 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''June 14\u2013June 16, at [[2019 Baltimore Orioles season|Baltimore Orioles]]'''\n\nIn the opener of a three-game series in Baltimore, Boston had 16 hits including six home runs, for a 13\u20132 win. [[Eduardo Rodr\u00edguez (left-handed pitcher)|Eduardo Rodr\u00edguez]] held the Orioles to one run in seven innings, improving his record on the season to 7\u20134. The second game was scoreless until the sixth inning, with the Red Sox taking a 3\u20132 lead, en route to a 7\u20132 final. [[Chris Sale]] got the win and improved his record to 3\u20137, while [[J. D. Martinez]] hit his 16th home run of the season. Boston trailed Baltimore, 3\u20132, going into the ninth inning of the final game of the series, when a home run by [[Marco Hern\u00e1ndez]] tied the game and sent it to [[extra innings]]. The Red Sox then outscored the Orioles, 5\u20133, in the extra frame, giving Boston an 8\u20136 victory and their fifth consecutive win.\n\n<small>'''Red Sox won the series 3\u20130 (28\u201310 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''June 17\u2013June 19, at [[2019 Minnesota Twins season|Minnesota Twins]]'''\n[[File:Ryan David Brasier.jpg|thumb|right|upright|[[Ryan Brasier]] notched his seventh save on June 17.]]\nBoston extended their winning streak to six games, with a 2\u20130 win in the series' opener in Minnesota. The only runs of the game came on three singles to open the game, and a pair of ninth-inning doubles. [[Rick Porcello]] improved his record to 5\u20136, while [[Ryan Brasier]] recorded his seventh [[Save (baseball)|save]] of the year. The second game of the series was Boston's longest to this point in the season, as the teams were tied, 2\u20132, at the end of regulation. In the 13th inning, [[Mookie Betts]] homered for the Red Sox and [[Max Kepler]] homered for the Twins, leaving the game still tied, 3\u20133. Although [[Andrew Benintendi]] reached third base with no outs in the top of the 17th, he was left stranded there. In the bottom of the inning, the Twins loaded the bases with one out on a single, a double, and an intentional walk; Kepler then drove in the winning run with a single to right field. [[J. D. Martinez]] and Twins third baseman [[Miguel Sano]] each struck out five times in the game.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/mlb/boxscore?gameId=401075830 |title=Red Sox vs. Twins - Box Score |website=[[ESPN]] |date=June 18, 2019 |accessdate=June 19, 2019}}</ref> Minnesota led the final game of the series, 4\u20133, after four innings. Boston then scored the final six runs of the game for the win, 9\u20134. [[Eduardo Rodr\u00edguez (left-handed pitcher)|Eduardo Rodr\u00edguez]] improved his season record to 8\u20134.\n\n<small>'''Red Sox won the series 2\u20131 (14\u20138 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''June 21\u2013June 23, vs. [[2019 Toronto Blue Jays season|Toronto Blue Jays]]'''<br>\nIn the series' opener, the Red Sox fell behind, 4\u20131, at the end of four innings. At the end of seven, Toronto still led, 5\u20134, but Boston tied the game in the eighth, and the game went to [[extra innings]]. [[Christian V\u00e1zquez]] then hit a two-run [[walk-off home run]] in the bottom of the tenth, giving the Red Sox a 7\u20135 win. Boston held a 6\u20130 lead after three innings in the second game of the series, only to have Toronto go ahead, 8\u20136, in the eighth inning. A Red Sox rally in the ninth inning came up a run short, resulting in an 8\u20137 loss. Boston's bullpen allowed seven runs in the final four innings. The final game of the series was a 6\u20131 Blue Jays win, as the Red Sox did not score until the ninth inning.\n\n<small>'''Red Sox lost the series 1\u20132 (15\u201319 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''June 24\u2013June 26, vs. [[2019 Chicago White Sox season|Chicago White Sox]]'''<br>\nTrailing 2\u20131 after four innings of the first game of the series, Boston scored a single run in each remaining inning, for a 6\u20135 win. The winning run came on an infield single by [[Marco Hern\u00e1ndez]] with the bases loaded and two outs in the bottom of the ninth. Start time of the second game of the series was delayed for 24 minutes by rain. The teams then traded early runs, and were tied 3\u20133 after three innings. The Red Sox went on to score the final three runs of the game, for a 6\u20133 win. [[Xander Bogaerts]] hit his 15th home run of the season, while starter [[David Price (baseball)|David Price]] improved his record to 5\u20132. Boston was unable to complete the sweep on Wednesday afternoon, as Chicago scored two runs in the top of the ninth inning via a [[Jos\u00e9 Abreu (baseball)|Jos\u00e9 Abreu]] homer for an 8\u20137 win. [[Matt Barnes (baseball)|Matt Barnes]] was charged with his sixth [[blown save]] of the season, and took the loss. The White Sox had early leads of 3\u20132 and 5\u20133, while the Red Sox had gone ahead, 7\u20136, via three runs in the bottom of the eighth.\n\n<small>'''Red Sox won the series 2\u20131 (19\u201316 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''June 29\u2013June 30, vs. [[2019 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]]''' in [[London]], [[United Kingdom]]<br>\n{{more|2019 MLB London Series}}\nThe first MLB game played in Europe opened with the Yankees scoring six runs in the top of the first inning, chasing Boston starter [[Rick Porcello]] after one-third of an inning. The Red Sox responded with six runs of their own in the bottom of the first, as New York starter [[Masahiro Tanaka]] only lasted two-thirds of an inning. The Yankees built a 17\u20136 lead through five innings, which the Red Sox narrowed to 17\u201313 at the end of the seventh, but there was no further scoring. [[Michael Chavis]] had a pair of three-run home runs, while [[Jackie Bradley Jr.]] also homered. At 4 hours 42 minutes, the game was only three minutes shorter than the longest nine-inning game in MLB history (August 18, 2006, also between the Red Sox and Yankees).<ref>{{cite tweet |user=TomCaron |number=1145077444967391232 |title=The longest 9-inning game in #MLB history was on Aug. 18, 2006.  It lasted 4:45. |date=June 29, 2019 |accessdate=June 29, 2019}}</ref> In the second and final game of the series, the Red Sox jumped out to a 4\u20130 first-inning lead. The Yankees scored two runs in the second, and it remained 4\u20132 until the seventh inning, when New York scored nine runs, giving them an 11\u20134 lead. Boston closed to 12\u20138 in the bottom of the eighth, and had the bases loaded with two outs, but there was no further scoring. The loss, Boston's third in a row, left the team with a 44\u201340 record at the end of June, 11 games behind New York in the [[American League East]] standings.\n\n<small>'''Red Sox lost the series 0\u20132 (21\u201329 runs)'''</small>\n{{collapse bottom}}\n\n{{collapse top|title=July}}\n\n===July===\n'''July 2\u2013July 4, at [[2019 Toronto Blue Jays season|Toronto Blue Jays]]'''\n\nIn the opening game of the series, Boston scored four runs in the top of the first inning, and built a 7\u20131 lead en route to a 10\u20136 victory. Starting pitcher [[David Price (baseball)|David Price]] limited the Blue Jays to four hits and two runs in six innings. [[Rafael Devers]] had two home runs and six RBIs, while [[Christian V\u00e1zquez]] went 3-for-5 with a homer. The second game of the series was tied, 3\u20133, after four innings. The only further scoring was three runs by the Blue Jays, handing the Red Sox a 6\u20133 defeat. V\u00e1zquez hit his 13th home run of the season, [[Chris Sale]] saw his record fall to 3\u20138, and [[Xander Bogaerts]] had a [[golden sombrero]] (four strikeouts) for the first time in his career.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=RSNStats |number=1146596059558420480 |title=4th strikeout of the game for #RedSox Xander Bogaerts. 842nd career game but the first ever golden sombrero for Bogaerts. |date=July 3, 2019 |accessdate=July 3, 2019}}</ref> In the final game of the series, a nine-run sixth inning and a [[pinch hitter|pinch hit]] home run by [[Marco Hern\u00e1ndez]] in the ninth gave Boston an 8\u20137 win. Devers and [[Michael Chavis]] also homered.\n\n<small>'''Red Sox won the series 2\u20131 (21\u201319 runs)'''</small>\n\n[[File:Christian V\u00e1zquez in 2017 (37215301271).jpg|thumb|right|upright|[[Christian V\u00e1zquez]] had 14 home runs at the All-Star break.]]\n'''July 5\u2013July 7, at [[2019 Detroit Tigers season|Detroit Tigers]]'''\n\nBoston won the opener of the series, 9\u20136, in a game that included a two-hour rain delay. [[Rafael Devers]] and [[Xander Bogaerts]] each homered, their 16th and 17th of the season, respectively. The start of the second game of the series was delayed by rain for four hours. Boston then jumped out to an early 5\u20130 lead, and went on to win, 10\u20136. [[Andrew Benintendi]] was 4-for-6 at the plate, only lacking a home run for the [[Hitting for the cycle|cycle]]. On Sunday, the Red Sox completed a series sweep with a 6\u20133 win. [[David Price (baseball)|David Price]] improved his record on the season to 7\u20132, and [[Christian V\u00e1zquez]] hit his 14th home run of the year. Boston reached the All-Star break with a record of 49\u201341 (0.544 [[winning percentage]]), nine [[games behind]] the division-leading Yankees, and two games behind Cleveland for the second [[Major League Baseball wild card|wild card]] spot.\n\n<small>'''Red Sox won the series 3\u20130 (25\u201315 runs)'''</small>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! July 9, [[2019 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star Game]] at [[Progressive Field]]\n|}\nIn a 4\u20133 American League win, all three Boston all-stars played, but were hitless. [[J. D. Martinez]] started at DH and was 0-for-2, [[Xander Bogaerts]] grounded out as a [[pinch hitter]], and [[Mookie Betts]] appeared as a defensive replacement without batting.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/mlb/boxscore?gameId=401076087 |title=All-Stars vs. All-Stars - Box-Score |website=[[ESPN]] |date=July 9, 2019 |accessdate=July 9, 2019}}</ref> [[Alex Cora]] managed the American League team, with assistance from his Red Sox coaches and [[Cleveland Indians]] manager [[Terry Francona]].<ref>{{cite new |url=https://www.masslive.com/redsox/2019/07/terry-francona-ex-boston-red-sox-manager-on-alex-coras-all-star-coaching-staff-im-going-to-enjoy-and-stay-the-heck-out-of-the-way.html |title=Terry Francona, ex-Boston Red Sox manager, on Alex Cora\u2019s All-Star coaching staff: \u2018I\u2019m going to enjoy and stay the heck out of the way\u2019 |first=Chris |last=Cotillo |website=masslive.com |date=July 9, 2019 |accessdate=July 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\n'''July 12\u2013July 14, vs. [[2019 Los Angeles Dodgers season|Los Angeles Dodgers]]'''\n\nIn this three-game series between the teams that contested the [[2018 World Series]], Boston won the opener, 8\u20131, in a game that included a one-hour rain delay. Red Sox starter [[Eduardo Rodr\u00edguez (left-handed pitcher)|Eduardo Rodr\u00edguez]] improved his record to 10\u20134 for the season, allowing only five hits and one run in seven innings. [[Rafael Devers]], [[Christian V\u00e1zquez]], and [[Xander Bogaerts]] each homered. The second game of the series was a one-run game entering the fifth inning, but turned into an 11\u20132 Dodgers' win. [[Chris Sale]] saw his record for the season fall to 3\u20139; Bogaerts had Boston's only home run and both RBIs. In the final game of the series, Boston fought back from a 4\u20132 deficit to tie the game in the eighth; the game then went to [[extra innings]]. The Red Sox were not able to capitalize on a leadoff double by [[Jackie Bradley Jr.]] in the 11th. The Dodgers went on to score three runs in the 12th, giving Boston a 7\u20134 loss. Duration of the game was five hours and 40 minutes.\n\n<small>'''Red Sox lost the series 1\u20132 (14\u201319 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''July 15\u2013July 18, vs. [[2019 Toronto Blue Jays season|Toronto Blue Jays]]'''\n\nThe first game in this four-game series was a 10\u20138 Boston win; a two-run victory after the Red Sox had held leads of 5\u20130 and 10\u20134. Eight different Red Sox players scored, and  [[Michael Chavis]] hit his first MLB [[grand slam (baseball)|grand slam]]. Toronto won the second game, 10\u20134, as [[Andrew Cashner]] took the loss in his first start with Boston, having allowed six runs (five earned) on eight hits in five innings. [[Xander Bogaerts]] hit his 21st home run of the season. The Red Sox won the third game, 5\u20134, with [[Eduardo Rodr\u00edguez (left-handed pitcher)|Eduardo Rodr\u00edguez]] improving his record on the season to 11\u20134. [[Rafael Devers]] went 3-for-4 at the plate, including his 18th home run of the year, and had four RBIs. Boston won the final game of the series, 5\u20130, with [[Chris Sale]] getting his first win at [[Fenway Park]] since July 11, 2018.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/sports/redsox/2019/07/18/redsox/ue2bGBWKMIDcvQw4QJ0BTP/story.html |title=Chris Sale snaps long drought with first regular-season win at Fenway in more than a year |first=Alex |last=Speier |website=[[The Boston Globe]] |url-access=limited |date=July 18, 2019 |accessdate=July 18, 2019}}</ref> Devers and [[Mookie Betts]] both homered.\n\n<small>'''Red Sox won the series 3\u20131 (24\u201322 runs)'''</small>\n\n[[File:Jackie Bradley Jr. in 2017 (36547479673).jpg|thumb|right|upright|[[Jackie Bradley Jr.]] had a pair of three-run homers on July 20.]]\n'''July 19\u2013July 21, at [[2019 Baltimore Orioles season|Baltimore Orioles]]'''\n\nBaltimore won the opener of this three-game series, 11\u20132, as Boston's only runs came on a second-inning two-run homer by [[Sam Travis]]. In the middle game of the series, Boston took an early 5\u20130 lead, with Baltimore tying the game, 5\u20135, in the third inning. Boston then scored eight runs in the fourth inning, en route to a 17\u20136 win. [[Jackie Bradley Jr.]] hit a pair of three-run home runs; [[Rafael Devers]], [[Mookie Betts]], and [[Sandy Le\u00f3n]] also homered. Baltimore took the closing game of the series, 5\u20130, as the Red Sox were held to one hit, a seventh-inning double by Devers.\n\n<small>'''Red Sox lost the series 1\u20132 (19\u201322 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''July 22\u2013July 24, at [[2019 Tampa Bay Rays season|Tampa Bay Rays]]'''\n\nBoston won the series' first game, 9\u20134, mainly powered by a seven-run third inning, which saw [[J. D. Martinez]], [[Andrew Benintendi]], and [[Sam Travis]] each homer. [[Eduardo Rodr\u00edguez (left-handed pitcher)|Eduardo Rodr\u00edguez]] improved his record on the season to 12\u20134. The second game was also a Boston win, 5\u20134. [[Christian V\u00e1zquez]] had a [[pinch hitter|pinch hit]] home run, and the Red Sox reached 10 games over .500 (56\u201346) for the first time this season. The final game of the series included a formal protest by the Red Sox, \"due to placement of substitutes in the lineup following the removal of the DH.\"<ref>{{cite tweet |user=alexspeier |number=1154108809511616512 |title=Red Sox are playing under protest |date=July 24, 2019 |accessdate=July 24, 2019}}</ref> On the field, Boston had a 2\u20130 lead through three innings, however the Rays then scored three unanswered runs to win, 3\u20132.\n\n<small>'''Red Sox won the series 2\u20131 (16\u201311 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''July 25\u2013July 28, vs. [[2019 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]]'''\n\nIn the opener of a four-game series, the Red Sox scored seven runs in the first inning and went on to a 19\u20133 win, setting a franchise record for the most runs scored in a game against the Yankees.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=TomCaron |number=1154579217079779328 |title=19 runs is a season high for the #RedSox, and the most ever in a game against the #Yankees. |date=July 25, 2019 |accessdate=July 25, 2019}}</ref> Boston had 10 doubles,<ref>{{cite tweet |user=dakern74 |number=1154590012194861057 |title=Red Sox: Second game in live-ball era where they collected 10 doubles. Other was a 13-3 win at Tiger Stadium on Jul 29 1990. |date=July 25, 2019 |accessdate=July 25, 2019}}</ref> including two by [[Michael Chavis]], who entered the game after [[Brock Holt]] was ejected.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=IanMBrowne |number=1154556125187956736 |title=Chavis, in the game because Holt got ejected |date=July 25, 2019 |accessdate=July 25, 2019}}</ref> [[Xander Bogaerts]] had two home runs, while [[Rafael Devers]] and [[Sandy Le\u00f3n]] also homered. In the second game of the series, Boston scored three first-inning runs, led 7\u20130 after four innings, and went on to a 10\u20135 win. [[Andrew Cashner]] held the Yankees to three runs on 10 hits in {{frac|6|2|3}} innings. [[Mookie Betts]] had the fifth three-homer game of his career,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://mlb.nbcsports.com/2019/07/26/watch-mookie-betts-belts-three-home-runs-in-first-three-at-bats/ |title=Watch: Mookie Betts belts three home runs in first three at-bats |first=Ashley |last=Varela |website=[[NBC Sports]] |date=July 26, 2019 |accessdate=July 26, 2019}}</ref> and [[J. D. Martinez]] also homered. The Red Sox reached 11 games over .500 (58\u201347) for the first time this year.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=PeteAbe |number=1154941067285925888 |title=Sox now 58-47, 11 games over .500 for the first time this season. |date=July 26, 2019 |accessdate=July 26, 2019}}</ref> Boston also won the third game of the series, 9\u20135, with Martinez and [[Andrew Benintendi]] hitting home runs.  The Red Sox were unable to complete the sweep, as the Yankees won Sunday's game, 9\u20136. The two teams combined for five errors, including a throwing error by [[Jackie Bradley Jr.]] that allowed two runs to score.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=NewsBronx |number=1155649202921377792 |title=That was an ugly play for the #RedSox |date=July 28, 2019 |accessdate=July 28, 2019}}</ref> Benintendi again homered, while [[Chris Sale]] saw his record fall to 5\u201310 on the season.\n\n<small>'''Red Sox won the series 3\u20131 (44\u201322 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''July 30\u2013July 31, vs. [[2019 Tampa Bay Rays season|Tampa Bay Rays]]'''\n\nBoston scored two first-inning runs in the opening game of the series and held a 5\u20134 lead after five innings, but fell to Tampa Bay, 6\u20135. The Red Sox left seven runners on base in the final three innings. [[Andrew Benintendi]] homered for the third consecutive game.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=RSNStats |number=1156373968938553345 |title=Career-best THIRD straight game with a home run for #RedSox Andrew Benintendi. |date=July 30, 2019 |accessdate=July 30, 2019}}</ref> In the series' second game, the Rays had a 5\u20130 lead after two innings, and went on to an 8\u20135 win. [[J. D. Martinez]] and [[Michael Chavis]] each homered. Boston finished July with three consecutive losses; at 59\u201350, the team was 10 [[games behind]] the division-leading Yankees, and {{frac|2|1|2}} games out of the second [[Major League Baseball wild card|wild card]] spot.\n\n{{collapse bottom}}\n\n{{collapse top|title=August}}\n\n===August===\n'''August 1, vs. [[2019 Tampa Bay Rays season|Tampa Bay Rays]] (cont'd)'''\n\nTampa Bay completed their sweep of the three-game series with a 9\u20134 win. [[Xander Bogaerts]] had two home runs, and [[Mookie Betts]] also homered. [[Andrew Benintendi]] was 3-for-4 at the plate with three doubles. With four losses in a row, Boston fell to 59\u201351 on the season.\n\n<small>'''Red Sox lost the series 0\u20133 (14\u201323 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''August 2\u20134, at [[2019 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]]'''\n\nThe opening game of this series\u2014with four games to be played in three days, due to a rainout earlier in the season\u2014was won by New York, 4\u20132. All scoring occurred in the first inning, with Boston's runs coming on a [[J. D. Martinez]] home run with [[Xander Bogaerts]] on base. The Red Sox' losing streak reached five games, for the first time since their [[2015 Boston Red Sox season|2015 season]]. New York won the second game of the series, 9\u20132, in the first game of a Saturday [[Doubleheader (baseball)|doubleheader]]. Boston's two runs came on solo homers by [[Jackie Bradley Jr.]] and [[Andrew Benintendi]]. Red Sox manager [[Alex Cora]] and starting pitcher [[Chris Sale]] were both [[Ejection (sports)|ejected]] in the fourth inning.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.masslive.com/redsox/2019/08/alex-cora-chris-sale-ejected-boston-red-sox-manager-pitcher-tossed-in-fourth-inning-vs-yankees.html |title=Alex Cora, Chris Sale ejected: Boston Red Sox manager, pitcher tossed in fourth inning vs. Yankees |first=Chris |last=Cotillo |website=masslive.com |date=August 3, 2019 |accessdate=August 3, 2019}}</ref> A 6\u20134 loss to the Yankees in the second game of the doubleheader gave the Red Sox their seventh loss in a row. [[Rafael Devers]] hit his 22nd home run of the season. The Yankees completed the sweep on Sunday evening with a 7\u20134 win. [[Christian V\u00e1zquez]] and [[Michael Chavis]] both homered, as the Red Sox' losing streak reached eight games.\n\n<small>'''Red Sox lost the series 0\u20134 (12\u201326 runs)'''</small>\n\n{{anchor|August7}}'''August 5\u20137, vs. [[2019 Kansas City Royals season|Kansas City Royals]]'''\n\nThe Red Sox ended their losing streak with a 7\u20135 win in the first of three games against the Royals. [[Sam Travis]] and [[Rafael Devers]] each homered, with [[Brandon Workman]] recording his sixth [[Save (baseball)|save]] of the year. Kansas City won the second game of the series, 6\u20132, scoring all their runs off of Boston starter [[Andrew Cashner]] in {{frac|5|1|3}} innings. The final game of the series saw Boston take a 4\u20132 lead through five innings, with Kansas City coming back to tie the game, 4\u20134, after seven innings. With no further scoring in regulation, the game went to [[extra innings]], and entered a rain delay in the top of the 10th inning. At approximately 12:30&nbsp;a.m., the game was officially [[Suspended game|suspended]]\u2014the Royals returned to Fenway on August 22 at 1:05&nbsp;p.m. to complete the game.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=alexspeier |number=1159322551694364672 |title=Suspended! Game to be resumed on Thursday, August 22 at 1:05 pm. |date=August 8, 2019 |accessdate=August 8, 2019}}</ref> For completion of the game and series, see [[#August22|August 22]].\n\n<small>'''Series was tied 1\u20131, pending completion of suspended game'''</small>\n\n'''August 8\u201311, vs. [[2019 Los Angeles Angels season|Los Angeles Angels]]'''\n\nThe first game of the four-game series was won by Boston, 3\u20130. [[Chris Sale]] held Los Angeles to two hits in eight innings, improving his record on the year to 6\u201311. Red Sox scoring came on a two-run homer by [[Sam Travis]] and a solo homer by [[Sandy Le\u00f3n]]. Boston won the second game, 16\u20134, while also outhitting the Angels, 14\u20133. [[J. D. Martinez]] was 4-for-5 at the plate, with two home runs and two doubles. [[Mookie Betts]], [[Rafael Devers]], and [[Mitch Moreland]] also homered. The Angels responded to their 12-run loss on Friday with an 8-run win on Saturday, 12\u20134. [[Sam Travis]] hit his fifth home run of the season. Los Angeles took an early 3\u20130 lead in the final game of the series, with Boston going ahead, 4\u20133, after five innings. An eighth-inning run by the Angels tied the game, which went to [[extra innings]]; a tenth-inning run gave Los Angeles the win, 5\u20134. [[Christian V\u00e1zquez]] hit his 18th home run of the season.\n\n<small>'''Red Sox tied the series 2\u20132 (27\u201321 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''August 12\u201314, at [[2019 Cleveland Indians season|Cleveland Indians]]'''<br>\n[[File:Chris Sale in 2017 (37185846582) (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|upright|[[Chris Sale]] recorded his 2,000th MLB strikeout on August 13.]]\nIn the series' opening game, Boston trailed, 5\u20131, after three innings. Two runs by the Red Sox in the fourth, one in the seventh, and one in the ninth resulted in a 5\u20135 tie. In the bottom of the ninth, Cleveland's [[Carlos Santana (baseball)|Carlos Santana]] hit a [[walk-off home run]], giving Boston their third loss in a row. Boston built a 6\u20131 lead midway through the sixth inning of the second game of the series, only to have Cleveland tie the game and force [[extra innings]]. A home run by [[Jackie Bradley Jr.]] in the top of the 10th inning proved to be the difference in a 7\u20136 Red Sox win. [[Andrew Cashner]] was used in relief and got the [[Save (baseball)|save]], the first of his MLB career.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=TomCaron |number=1161479820611608578 |title=Cashner got his first MLB save. |date=August 13, 2019 |accessdate=August 14, 2019}}</ref> [[Chris Sale]] recorded the 2,000th strikeout of his MLB career.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=RedSox |number=1161435011318517760 |title=Chris Sale reached 2,000 career strikeouts in 1,626 IP. |date=August 13, 2019 |accessdate=August 14, 2019}}</ref> [[Rafael Devers]] became the latest MLB player to record [[List of Major League Baseball single-game hits leaders|six hits in a game]]; he was 5-for-5 in the first nine innings, and had his sixth hit in the 10th inning.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/CLE/CLE201908130.shtml|title=August 13, 2019 Boston Red Sox at Cleveland Indians Play by Play and Box Score|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|date=August 13, 2019|accessdate=August 14, 2019}}</ref> The Red Sox won the third and final game of the series, 5\u20131. Devers homered, and [[Xander Bogaerts]] hit two home runs.\n\n<small>'''Red Sox won the series 2\u20131 (17\u201313 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''August 16\u201318, vs. [[2019 Baltimore Orioles season|Baltimore Orioles]]'''\n\nThe opening game of the series was a 9\u20131 Boston win, as the Red Sox outhit the Orioles, 12\u20135. [[Mookie Betts]] hit his 21st home run of the season. Boston extended their winning streak to four games with a 4\u20130 win in the middle game of the series. [[Eduardo Rodr\u00edguez (left-handed pitcher)|Eduardo Rodr\u00edguez]] improved his record on the season to 14\u20135, while [[Brock Holt]] and [[Rafael Devers]] each homered. Boston completed the sweep on Sunday, coming back from a 6\u20130 deficit to record a 13\u20137 win. Devers and [[Sam Travis]] each homered, as Boston used seven pitchers, with [[Marcus Walden]] getting the win. Devers became the first MLB players to reach 100 RBIs on the season.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=RedSox_Report |number=1163218704785690626 |title=Red Sox third baseman Rafael Devers MLB\u2019s first to 100 RBI in 2019 |date=August 18, 2019 |accessdate=August 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\n<small>'''Red Sox won the series 3\u20130 (26\u20138 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''August 20\u201321, vs. [[2019 Philadelphia Phillies season|Philadelphia Phillies]]'''\n\nBoston lost the opening inter-league game against Philadelphia, 3\u20132. All three Phillies runs came in the first inning, from a walk, two doubles, and a single. Both Red Sox runs came in the third inning, as [[Jackie Bradley Jr.]] hit a two-run homer. Boston's five-game winning streak ended as the team fell to 67\u201360 on the season. Philadelphia then swept the two-game series with a 5\u20132 win, despite the Red Sox outhitting the Phillies, 8\u20136. Bradley Jr. homered again, his 16th of the season. [[Rick Porcello]] took the loss and fell to 11\u201310 on the season.\n\n<small>'''Red Sox lost the series 0\u20132 (4\u20138 runs)'''</small>\n\n{{anchor|August22}}'''August 22, vs. [[2019 Kansas City Royals season|Kansas City Royals]]'''\n\nThis was the resumption of the [[suspended game]] from [[#August7|August 7]], which was halted due to rain with no outs in the top of the 10th with no runners on base and the score tied, 4\u20134.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/mlb/playbyplay?gameId=401076445 |title=Royals vs. Red Sox - Play-By-Play |website=[[ESPN]] |date=August 7, 2019 |accessdate=August 21, 2019}}</ref> The Red Sox allowed anyone under 18 years old to enter [[Fenway Park]] for free; all other tickets were only $5 each, with proceeds going to [[The Jimmy Fund]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://boston.cbslocal.com/2019/08/16/red-sox-admitting-children-free-continuation-suspended-game-vs-royals/ |title=Red Sox Admitting Children For Free, Adults For $5 To Continuation Of Suspended Game Vs. Royals |website=[[WBZ-TV]] |date=August 16, 2019 |accessdate=August 16, 2019}}</ref> After retiring the Royals in order in the top of the 10th, [[Christian V\u00e1zquez]] hit a one-out double, which was followed by an [[Intentional base on balls|intentional walk]] and then a game-winning single by [[Brock Holt]].\n\n<small>'''Red Sox won the series 2\u20131 (14\u201315 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''August 23\u201325, at [[2019 San Diego Padres season|San Diego Padres]]'''\n[[File:J. D. Martinez Boston Red Sox August 2018 (crop).png|thumb|right|upright|[[J. D. Martinez]] had seven RBIs on August 23.]]\nThis three-game series was held on [[Players Weekend]], when MLB players are allowed and encouraged to put nicknames on the back of their uniforms. For the opening game, the nicknames used by Boston's starting lineup were as follows:<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/2019-mlb-players-weekend-nicknames |title=Every team's Players' Weekend nicknames |website=[[MLB.com]] |date=August 21, 2019 |accessdate=August 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/mlb/boxscore?gameId=401076655 |title=Red Sox vs. Padres - Box Score |website=[[ESPN]] |date=August 23, 2019 |accessdate=August 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n<small>\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! Order || No. || Player || Nickname || Pos.\n|-\n| 1 || 50 || [[Mookie Betts]] || MOOKIE || CF\n|-\n| 2 || 11 || [[Rafael Devers]] || {{abbr|CARITA|\"baby face\"}} || 3B\n|-\n| 3 || &nbsp;2 || [[Xander Bogaerts]] || X-MAN || SS\n|-\n| 4 || 28 || [[J. D. Martinez]] || {{abbr|FLACO|\"skinny\"}} ||RF\n|-\n| 5 || 16 || [[Andrew Benintendi]] || BENNY || LF\n|-\n| 6 || &nbsp;7 || [[Christian V\u00e1zquez]] || COLO || C\n|-\n| 7 || 18 || [[Mitch Moreland]] || 2-BAGS || 1B\n|-\n| 8 || 12 || [[Brock Holt]] || BH || 2B\n|-\n| 9 || 57 || [[Eduardo Rodr\u00edguez (left-handed pitcher)|Eduardo Rodr\u00edguez]] || EL GUALO || P\n|}\n</small>\n\nIn the opening game, Boston scored three runs in each of the first two innings, and went on to an 11\u20130 win. [[Eduardo Rodr\u00edguez (left-handed pitcher)|Eduardo Rodr\u00edguez]] got the win and improved his record on the season to 15\u20135. [[J. D. Martinez]] hit a pair of three-run homers, going 3-for-4 at the plate with seven RBIs. In the middle game of the series, the Red Sox had a 4\u20133 lead after four innings. San Diego tied the game with a run in the seventh, then [[Brock Holt]]'s ninth-inning home run provided Boston's winning margin, 5\u20134. The Red Sox were unable to complete the sweep on Sunday, falling to the Padres, 3\u20131. Boston's run came on the 31st homer of the season by Martinez.\n\n<small>'''Red Sox won the series 2\u20131 (17\u20137 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''August 27\u201328, at [[2019 Colorado Rockies season|Colorado Rockies]]'''\n\nIn this inter-league series, Boston took a 6\u20130 lead in the first game, and went on to a 10\u20136 win. [[Jackie Bradley Jr.]], [[Christian V\u00e1zquez]], and [[Xander Bogaerts]] each homered. At an estimated distance of {{convert|478|ft|m}}, the homer by Bradley Jr. was the longest by a Red Sox player since [[Statcast]] was introduced in 2015.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=RSNStats |number=1166570634136182785 |title=Tonight's home run by #RedSox Jackie Bradley, Jr. |date=August 28, 2019 |accessdate=August 28, 2019}}</ref> Boston completed the two-game sweep with a 7\u20134 win, as [[Eduardo Rodr\u00edguez (left-handed pitcher)|Eduardo Rodr\u00edguez]] got his 16th win of the season. Bogaerts hit two home runs, becoming the first Red Sox [[shortstop]] with 30 in a season since [[Nomar Garciaparra]] in 1998.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=PeteAbe |number=1166914851022749698 |title=Second homer of the game and third in two nights for Bogaerts. |date=August 28, 2019 |accessdate=August 29, 2019}}</ref> [[J. D. Martinez]] and [[Rafael Devers]] also homered.\n\n<small>'''Red Sox won the series 2\u20130 (17\u201310 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''August 30\u2013August 31, at [[2019 Los Angeles Angels season|Los Angeles Angels]]'''\n\nIn the series' opener, Boston took an early 4\u20130 lead, and had a 6\u20134 lead going to the bottom of the ninth inning, only to see the Angels tie the game and force [[extra innings]]. The tie held until [[Mookie Betts]] hit his second home run of the game in the top of the 15th inning, which proved to be the difference as the Red Sox won, 7\u20136. Duration of the game was 5 hours 23 minutes, and included the 33rd homer of the season by [[J. D. Martinez]]. In the middle game of the series, the Red Sox held a 4\u20133 lead after seven innings. In the bottom of the eighth, the Angels scored seven runs, and went on to win, 10\u20134. The loss left Boston with an overall record of 73\u201363, having accrued a record of 14\u201313 during August.\n\n{{collapse bottom}}\n\n{{collapse top|title=September}}\n\n===September===\nWith [[expanded roster]]s allowed starting on September 1, the team added four pitchers ([[Jhoulys Chac\u00edn]], [[Travis Lakins]], [[Ryan Weber]], and [[H\u00e9ctor Vel\u00e1zquez (baseball)|H\u00e9ctor Vel\u00e1zquez]]) and two position players (catcher [[Juan Centeno]] and outfielder [[Gorkys Hern\u00e1ndez]]).<ref name=Callups/> Following the end of the [[Triple-A (baseball)|Triple-A]] season, on September 4 the team added four additional pitchers ([[Colten Brewer]], [[Trevor Kelley]], [[Bobby Poyner]], and [[Mike Shawaryn]]).<ref name=Callups>{{cite web |url=http://m.redsox.mlb.com/roster/transactions/2019/09 |title=Red Sox Roster & Staff \u2013 Transactions |date=September 2019 |website=[[MLB.com]] |accessdate=September 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\n'''September 1, at [[2019 Los Angeles Angels season|Los Angeles Angels]] (cont'd)'''\n\nBoston won the third game of the series, 4\u20133. [[Xander Bogaerts]] and [[J. D. Martinez]] each homered, with Bogaerts going 3-for-4 with three RBIs. [[Brandon Workman]] recorded his 10th [[Save (baseball)|save]] of the season.\n\n<small>'''Red Sox won the series 2\u20131 (15\u201319 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''September 3\u20135, vs. [[2019 Minnesota Twins season|Minnesota Twins]]'''\n\nIn the first game of the series, Minnesota took a 6\u20130 lead through the middle of the fifth inning. Boston closed to 6\u20134 at the end of the fifth, and to 6\u20135 at the end of the eighth. Despite a leadoff single in the bottom of the ninth, the Red Sox were unable to score again. [[Rick Porcello]] fell to 12\u201311 on the season, while [[Rafael Devers]] and [[Andrew Benintendi]] both homered. Boston won the second game of the series, 6\u20132, as [[Mookie Betts]] had two home runs, including one to leadoff the game. [[Eduardo Rodr\u00edguez (left-handed pitcher)|Eduardo Rodr\u00edguez]] got his 17th win of the season, and [[Brandon Workman]] got his 11th [[Save (baseball)|save]]. The final game of the series was a 2\u20131 win by the Twins. The Red Sox had the tying run on base in the ninth inning, but Devers was thrown out at the plate trying to score on a two-out double that [[J. D. Martinez]] hit off of the [[Green Monster]]. Boston's run came on a Betts homer that hit [[Pesky's Pole]].\n\n<small>'''Red Sox lost the series 1\u20132 (12\u201310 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''September 6\u20139, vs. [[2019 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]]'''\n[[File:Red Sox President of Baseball Operations David Dombrowski (23655867925).jpg|thumb|right|upright|[[Dave Dombrowski]] was dismissed shortly after the September 8 loss to the Yankees.]]\n[[Jhoulys Chac\u00edn]] got the start in the first game of this four-game series, retiring all six batters he faced while striking out four. Powered mainly by a four-run fourth inning, Boston went on to win, 6\u20131, while using seven pitchers. [[Mitch Moreland]] hit his 15th home run of the season. The Yankees won the series' second game, 5\u20131, also mainly due to a four-run fourth inning. Boston's run came on a ninth-inning homer by [[J. D. Martinez]]. New York won the third game of the series, 10\u20135, scoring first and never trailing. [[Jackie Bradley Jr.]] and [[Mookie Betts]] each homered.\n\nFollowing the September 8 loss to the Yankees, which dropped the Red Sox to 76\u201367 on the season, the team dismissed president of baseball operations [[Dave Dombrowski]].<ref name=DombroOut/> The team announced that baseball operations would be run by assistant general managers [[Brian O'Halloran (baseball)|Brian O'Halloran]], Eddie Romero, and Zack Scott on an interim basis.<ref name=DombroOut>{{cite news |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/sports/redsox/2019/09/08/red-sox-part-ways-with-dave-dombrowski/MI6P23paliFaFMVRCoaqPN/story.html |title=Dave Dombrowski out as Red Sox president of baseball operations |first=Pete |last=Abraham |website=[[The Boston Globe]] |url-access=limited |date=September 9, 2019 |accessdate=September 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe final game of the series was a 5\u20130 Yankees win, which eliminated the Red Sox from [[American League East|AL East]] title contention.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=PeteAbe |number=1171251814265696263 |title=Sox eliminated in the AL East. They were 5-14 vs. the Yankees this season. |date=September 9, 2010 |accessdate=September 9, 2010}}</ref> Prior to the game, [[David Ortiz]] threw out the [[ceremonial first pitch]].<ref>{{cite tweet |user=OnlyInBOS |number=1171200877836853249 |title=David Ortiz threw out the first pitch tonight to Jason Varitek, his first public appearance since after the shooting on June 9th. |date=September 9, 2019 |accessdate=September 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\n<small>'''Red Sox lost the series 1\u20133 (12\u201321 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''September 10\u201312, at [[2019 Toronto Blue Jays season|Toronto Blue Jays]]'''\n\nThe first game of the series was a 4\u20133 win by Toronto, after Boston had held leads of 1\u20130 and 3\u20132. [[Mookie Betts]] hit his 28th home run of the season. The second game of the series was an 8\u20130 win by the Blue Jays, extending Boston's losing streak to five games. The Red Sox only collected two hits, one each by [[Brock Holt]] and [[Rafael Devers]]. Boston won the final game of the series, 7\u20134, with Blue Jay starter and former Red Sox pitcher [[Clay Buchholz]] taking the loss. Boston used nine pitchers, with [[Brandon Workman]] notching his 12th [[Save (baseball)|save]] of the season.\n\n<small>'''Red Sox lost the series 1\u20132 (10\u201316 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''September 14\u201315, at [[2019 Philadelphia Phillies season|Philadelphia Phillies]]'''\n\nIn this weekend inter-league series, Boston won the first game, 2\u20131. The winning run scored on a [[sacrifice fly]] by [[Andrew Benintendi]] in the top of the ninth inning. Boston also won the second game, 6\u20133. [[Christian V\u00e1zquez]] had a third-inning [[Grand slam (baseball)|grand slam]] and a sixth inning solo homer.\n\n<small>'''Red Sox won the series 2\u20130 (8\u20134 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''September 17\u201319, vs. [[2019 San Francisco Giants season|San Francisco Giants]]'''\n\nThe opening game of this three-game inter-league series featured the Giants' [[Mike Yastrzemski]], grandson of [[National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum|Hall of Fame]] inductee [[Carl Yastrzemski]] of the Red Sox; the younger Yastrzemski hit his 20th home run of the season in the fourth inning.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/carl-mike-yastrzemski-reunite-at-fenway-park |title=After Yaz reunion, Mike homers in Fenway debut |first=Jessica |last=Camerato |website=[[MLB.com]] |date=September 18, 2019 |accessdate=September 18, 2019}}</ref> San Francisco built a 5\u20131 lead through four innings, which became a 5\u20135 tie at the end of the sixth.  With no further scoring in regulation, the game went into [[extra innings]]. The teams traded runs in the 13th inning, and the Giants pushed across a run in the 15th inning, for a 7\u20136 win. With a game duration of 5 hours and 54 minutes, the teams used a total of 24 pitchers, tying the major league record,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/sports/redsox/2019/09/18/another-eovaldi-roller-coaster-outing-raises-questions/CbeC0h3LHnkST1Q4lk2FTL/story.html |title=Red Sox finally yield to Giants in 15-inning loss at Fenway |first=Alex |last=Speier |website=[[The Boston Globe]] |url-access=limited |date=September 18, 2019 |accessdate=September 18, 2019}}</ref> and 50 players total.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=PeteAbe |number=1174192209626894339 |title=50 players used tonight. |date=September 18, 2019 |accessdate=September 18, 2019}}</ref> The second game of the series was an 11\u20133 win by the Giants, the 2,000th win of manager [[Bruce Bochy]]'s career.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbssports.com/mlb/news/giants-bruce-bochy-becomes-11th-manager-with-2000-career-wins/ |title=Giants' Bruce Bochy becomes 11th manager with 2,000 career wins |first=Mike |last=Axisa |website=[[CBS Sports]] |date=September 18, 2019 |accessdate=September 18, 2019}}</ref> [[Rafael Devers]] hit his 30th home run of the season, while [[Jackie Bradley Jr.]] hit his 20th. Before the game, a [[ceremonial first pitch]] was thrown by Carl Yastrzemski to his grandson Mike.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/carl-yastrzemski-throws-first-pitch-to-grandson |title=Carl Yastrzemski throws first pitch to grandson |first=Jessica |last=Camerato |website=[[MLB.com]] |date=September 18, 2019 |accessdate=September 18, 2019}}</ref> The Red Sox won the final game of the series, 5\u20134, with [[Eduardo Rodr\u00edguez (left-handed pitcher)|Eduardo Rodr\u00edguez]] recording his 18th win of the season. All of Boston's run came in the first two innings. [[Xander Bogaerts]] was 2-for-4 with three RBIs, in his first MLB game as a [[designated hitter]].\n\n<small>'''Red Sox lost the series 1\u20132 (14\u201322 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''September 20\u201323, at [[2019 Tampa Bay Rays season|Tampa Bay Rays]]'''\n\nThe opening game of this four-game series was won in 11 innings by the Rays, 5\u20134. With the Rays defending [[Mitch Moreland]]'s at-bats with four outfielders,<ref>{{cite tweet |user=RecitsSox |number=1119728810721779714 |title=4 outfielders pour Mitch Moreland |date=September 20, 2019 |accessdate=September 20, 2019}}</ref> he hit two home runs and had all four RBIs for the Red Sox. A win by the [[2019 Cleveland Indians season|Cleveland Indians]] while Boston's game was in progress eliminated the Red Sox from postseason contention.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/sports/redsox/2019/09/20/redsox/Is3xtM8g7lvPq0hXYoC5lO/story.html |title=Rays stop Red Sox in 11 innings |first=Julian |last=McWilliams |website=[[The Boston Globe]] |url-access=limited |date=September 20, 2019 |accessdate=September 20, 2019}}</ref> The second game of the series was again a 5\u20134 Rays win in 11 innings. Tied 3\u20133 after nine innings, Moreland homered for Boston to take a 4\u20133 lead in the top of the 11th. With no outs and a runner on second in the bottom of the 11th, [[Nate Lowe]] hit a [[walk-off home run]] to give Tampa Bay the win. [[Xander Bogaerts]] and [[Rafael Devers]] both homered during regulation for Boston. The third game of the series was a 7\u20134 Boston win, with [[Nathan Eovaldi]] getting the win after holding the Rays to three runs in six innings. [[Christian V\u00e1zquez]] hit his 22nd home run of the season, going 3-for-5 with three RBIs. The final game of the series was won by the Rays, 7\u20134. The Red Sox led, 4\u20130, midway through the fourth inning; Tampa Bay then scored six in the bottom of the fourth, and held Boston scoreless for the rest of the game.\n\n<small>'''Red Sox lost the series 1\u20133 (19\u201321 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''September 24\u201326, at [[2019 Texas Rangers season|Texas Rangers]]'''\n\nThe opener of this three-game series was won by the Red Sox, 12\u201310, with [[Eduardo Rodr\u00edguez (left-handed pitcher)|Eduardo Rodr\u00edguez]] earning his 19th win of the season, despite allowing seven runs in five innings. [[Mookie Betts]] hit his 29th home run of the season, giving the team 238 homers for the season, tying the franchise record set by the [[2003 Boston Red Sox season|2003 Red Sox]].<ref>{{cite tweet |user=PeteAbe |number=1176709500046327811 |title=Sox tie team HR record with 238. |date=September 25, 2019 |accessdate=September 25, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet |user=PeteAbe |number=1175577412014411776 |title=Team record of 238 was set in 2003. |date=September 21, 2019 |accessdate=September 25, 2019}}</ref> Boston won the second game of the series, 10\u20133, with starter [[Rick Porcello]] improving his record on the season to 14\u201312. A third-inning home run by [[Christian V\u00e1zquez]] was the team's 239th of the season, setting a new franchise record.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.masslive.com/redsox/2019/09/boston-red-sox-break-franchise-record-for-home-runs-in-season-christian-vazquez-hits-teams-239th-blast-of-2019.html |title=Boston Red Sox break franchise record for home runs in season; Christian Vazquez hits team\u2019s 239th blast of 2019 |first=Chris |last=Cotillo |website=masslive.com |date=September 25, 2019 |accessdate=September 25, 2019}}</ref> [[Mitch Moreland]] and [[Rafael Devers]] added homers in later innings. The final game of the series was won by the Rangers, 7\u20135. [[Jackie Bradley Jr.]] and [[Chris Owings]] each homered for the Red Sox. This was Boston's final road game of the season; the team had an overall 46\u201335 record in away games.\n\n<small>'''Red Sox won the series 2\u20131 (27\u201320 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''September 27\u201329, vs. [[2019 Baltimore Orioles season|Baltimore Orioles]]'''\n\nThe final series of the season began with a 4\u20131 Baltimore win, as Boston's only run was driven in by [[Xander Bogaerts]] in the ninth inning. Baltimore also won the second game of the series, 9\u20134. Bogaerts and [[J. D. Martinez]] each homered for Boston. The final game of the season was a 5\u20134 Red Sox win, as [[Rafael Devers]] notched his 200th hit of the season.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.masslive.com/sports/2019/09/boston-red-soxs-rafael-devers-joins-whit-merrifield-as-only-mlb-players-with-200-hits-in-2019.html |title=Boston Red Sox\u2019s Rafael Devers joins Whit Merrifield as only MLB players with 200 hits in 2019 |first=Christopher |last=Smith |website=masslive.com |date=September 29, 2019 |accessdate=September 29, 2019}}</ref> [[Eduardo Rodr\u00edguez (left-handed pitcher)|Eduardo Rodr\u00edguez]], going for his 20th win of the season, had to settle for a [[no decision]]. [[Mookie Betts]] scored the winning run in the bottom of the ninth inning, scoring all the way from first on a ground ball that went into right field.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.eagletribune.com/sports/national_sports/betts-scores-wild-run-red-sox-end-season-with-walkoff/article_1c7cd021-13e9-50b3-93a6-7f28bc7053e3.html |title=Betts scores wild run, Red Sox end season with walkoff |first=Kyle |last=Hightower |agency=[[Associated Press|AP]] |website=[[The Eagle-Tribune]] |location=[[North Andover, Massachusetts]] |date=September 29, 2019 |accessdate=September 30, 2019}}</ref>\n\n<small>'''Red Sox lost the series 1\u20132 (10\u201317 runs)'''</small>\n<!--\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Probable starters\n|-\n! rowspan=2|Day & Time<br><small>All times [[Eastern Time Zone|ET]]</small>\n! colspan=4 style=\"{{Baseball primary style|Baltimore Orioles}};\"|Baltimore\n! colspan=4 style=\"{{Baseball primary style|Boston Red Sox}};\"|Boston\n! rowspan=2|Ref.\n|-\n! L/R !! Pitcher !! W\u2013L !! ERA !! L/R !! Pitcher !! W\u2013L !! ERA\n|-\n| Sun 3:05 p.m.\n| RHP || [[Chandler Shepherd]] || 0\u20130 || 7.71\n| LHP || [[Eduardo Rodr\u00edguez (left-handed pitcher)|Eduardo Rodr\u00edguez]] || 19\u20136 || 3.76\n| <ref>https://www.mlb.com/probable-pitchers/2019-09-29</ref>\n|}\n-->\n{{collapse bottom}}\n\n==Season standings==\n\n===American League East===\n{{2019 AL East standings|highlight=Boston Red Sox}}\n\n===American League Wild Card===\n{{2019 AL Wild Card standings|highlight=Boston Red Sox}}\n\n===Record against opponents===\n{{2019 AL Record vs. opponents|team=BOS}}\n\n==Roster==\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"text-align: left;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"10\" style=\"background-color: #ba313c; color: #FFFFFF; text-align: center;\" | 2019 Boston Red Sox\n|-\n| colspan=\"10\" style=\"background-color:#0d2b56; color: white; text-align: center;\" | '''Roster'''\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" | '''Pitchers'''\n{{MLBplayer|32|[[Matt Barnes (baseball)|Matt Barnes]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|70|[[Ryan Brasier]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|54|[[Colten Brewer]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|48|[[Andrew Cashner]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|43|[[Jhoulys Chac\u00edn]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|17|[[Nathan Eovaldi]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|37|[[Heath Hembree]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|63|[[Darwinzon Hern\u00e1ndez]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|61|[[Brian Johnson (pitcher)|Brian Johnson]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|71|[[Trevor Kelley]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|65,56|[[Travis Lakins]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|22|[[Rick Porcello]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|66|[[Bobby Poyner]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|10|[[David Price (baseball)|David Price]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|31|[[Erasmo Ram\u00edrez (right-handed pitcher)|Erasmo Ram\u00edrez]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|57|[[Eduardo Rodr\u00edguez (left-handed pitcher)|Eduardo Rodr\u00edguez]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|41|[[Chris Sale]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|73|[[Mike Shawaryn]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|67|[[Josh Smith (right-handed pitcher)|Josh Smith]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|72|[[Josh Taylor (baseball)|Josh Taylor]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|47|[[Tyler Thornburg]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|76|[[H\u00e9ctor Vel\u00e1zquez (baseball)|H\u00e9ctor Vel\u00e1zquez]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|64|[[Marcus Walden]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|65|[[Ryan Weber]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|44|[[Brandon Workman]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|35|[[Steven Wright (baseball)|Steven Wright]]}}\n\n| width=\"25px\" |\n| valign=\"top\" | '''Catchers'''\n{{MLBplayer|68|[[Juan Centeno]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|&nbsp;3|[[Sandy Le\u00f3n]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|23|[[Blake Swihart]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|&nbsp;7|[[Christian V\u00e1zquez]]}}\n'''Infielders'''\n{{MLBplayer|&nbsp;2|[[Xander Bogaerts]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|23|[[Michael Chavis]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|11|[[Rafael Devers]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|40|[[Marco Hern\u00e1ndez]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|12|[[Brock Holt]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|&nbsp;5|[[Tzu-Wei Lin]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|18|[[Mitch Moreland]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|36|[[Eduardo N\u00fa\u00f1ez]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|36|[[Chris Owings]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|25|[[Steve Pearce (baseball)|Steve Pearce]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|15|[[Dustin Pedroia]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|59|[[Sam Travis]]}}\n| width=\"25px\" |\n| valign=\"top\" | '''Outfielders'''\n{{MLBplayer|16|[[Andrew Benintendi]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|50|[[Mookie Betts]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|19|[[Jackie Bradley, Jr.]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|47|[[Gorkys Hern\u00e1ndez]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|28|[[J. D. Martinez]]}}\n| width=\"25px\" |\n| valign=\"top\" | '''Manager'''\n{{MLBplayer|20|[[Alex Cora]]}}\n'''Coaches'''\n{{MLBplayer|86|[[Brian Bannister]]}} {{small|(assistant pitching)}}\n{{MLBplayer|58|[[Andy Barkett]]}} {{small|(assistant hitting)}}\n{{MLBplayer|53|[[Craig Bjornson]]}} {{small|(bullpen/catching)}}\n{{MLBplayer|87|[[Bob Brenly#Personal life|Mike Brenly]]}} {{small|(bullpen catcher)}}\n{{MLBplayer|52|[[Carlos Febles]]}} {{small|(third base)}}\n{{MLBplayer|82|[[Tom Goodwin]]}} {{small|(first base/outfield)}}\n{{MLBplayer|51|[[Tim Hyers]]}} {{small|(hitting)}}\n{{MLBplayer|60|[[Dana LeVangie]]}} {{small|(pitching)}}\n{{MLBplayer|88|Mani Martinez}} {{small|(bullpen catcher)}}\n{{MLBplayer|30|[[Ron Roenicke]]}} {{small|(bench)}}\n{{MLBplayer|84|[[Ram\u00f3n V\u00e1zquez]]}} {{small|(coach)}}\n|}\n\n===MLB debuts===\nRed Sox players who made their MLB debuts during the 2019 regular season:\n* April 20: [[Michael Chavis]]\n* April 23: [[Darwinzon Hern\u00e1ndez]] and [[Travis Lakins]]\n* May 29: [[Josh Taylor (baseball)|Josh Taylor]]\n* June 7: [[Mike Shawaryn]]\n* July 2: [[Trevor Kelley]]\n\n===Transactions===\nNotable transactions of/for players on the [[40-man roster]] during the 2019 regular season:\n* April 16: Catcher [[Blake Swihart]] was [[designated for assignment]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/sports/redsox/2019/04/16/red-sox-designate-blake-swihart-for-assignment/Rr8jddNmzY555BsOj4RK8N/story.html |title=Red Sox designate Blake Swihart for assignment and bring up Sandy Leon |first=Peter |last=Abraham |website=[[The Boston Globe]] |url-access=limited |date=April 16, 2019 |accessdate=April 16, 2019}}</ref><ref name=AprilTrans>{{cite web |url=http://m.redsox.mlb.com/roster/transactions/2019/04 |title=Red Sox Roster & Staff \u2013 Transactions |website=[[MLB.com]] |date=April 2019 |accessdate=April 16, 2019}}</ref> He was traded to the [[Arizona Diamondbacks]] three days later, for minor league outfielder [[Marcus Wilson (baseball)|Marcus Wilson]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.fantasypros.com/mlb/news/210422/blake-swihart-traded-to-diamondbacks.php |title=Blake Swihart traded to the Diamondbacks |first=Kari |last=Thomas |website=fantasypros.com |date=April 19, 2019 |accessdate=April 19, 2019}}</ref>\n* July 10: Pitcher [[Tyler Thornburg]] was released.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=RedSox |number=1149009673737134083 |title=The #RedSox today released RHP Tyler Thornburg. |date=July 10, 2019 |accessdate=July 10, 2019}}</ref>\n* July 13: Boston acquired pitcher [[Andrew Cashner]] (and cash considerations) from the [[Baltimore Orioles]] in exchange for minor league position players Noelberth Romero and Elio Prado.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baltimoresun.com/sports/orioles/bs-sp-orioles-cashner-trade-20190713-vxcyy7f7hbd3la3fa3zvehzdyy-story.html|title=Orioles trade Andrew Cashner to Red Sox for two prospects|newspaper=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|author=Nathan Ruiz|date=July 13, 2019|accessdate=July 13, 2019}}</ref>\n* July 15: [[Eduardo N\u00fa\u00f1ez]] was designated for assignment;<ref>{{cite tweet |user=PeteAbe |number=1150830712519610368 |title=Eduardo Nunez DFA'd by the Red Sox. |date=July 15, 2019 |accessdate=July 15, 2019}}</ref> he was released on July 20.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=ChrisCotillo |number=1152631113929646080 |title=Red Sox released Eduardo Nunez, so he\u2019s now free to sign anywhere |date=July 20, 2019 |accessdate=July 22, 2019}}</ref>\n* September 1: The team activated pitcher [[Jhoulys Chac\u00edn]] when rosters expanded; Chac\u00edn had been signed to a minor league contract on August 31,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/sports/redsox/2019/09/01/red-sox-call-six-rosters-expand-for-september/AAVB7Wisz7pMLr5ISdGgiM/story.html |title=Red Sox call up six as rosters expand for September |first=Alex |last=Speier |website=[[The Boston Globe]] |url-access=limited |date=September 1, 2019 |accessdate=September 1, 2019}}</ref> after being released by the [[Milwaukee Brewers]] on August 26.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://m.brewers.mlb.com/roster/transactions/2019/08 |title=Brewers Roster & Staff \u2013 Transactions |website=[[MLB.com]] |date=August 2019 |accessdate=August 31, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Amateur draft===\nBoston's top ten selections in the [[2019 Major League Baseball draft|2019 MLB draft]], which started on June 3, are listed below.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mlb.com/draft/tracker/all/team/redsox |title=2019 Draft Tracker - Boston Red Sox |website=[[MLB.com]] |accessdate=June 4, 2019}}</ref> The team did not have a first-round pick, due to being more than $40 million over the [[Major League Baseball luxury tax|MLB luxury tax]] threshold.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.boston.com/sports/boston-red-sox/2019/06/03/major-league-baseball-draft |title=Why the Red Sox don\u2019t have a 1st-round pick in tonight\u2019s MLB Draft |first=Andrew |last=Mahoney |website=[[Boston.com]] |date=June 3, 2019 |accessdate=June 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size: 95%;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Round\n! scope=\"col\"| Pick\n! scope=\"col\"| Player\n! scope=\"col\"| Position\n! scope=\"col\"| B/T\n! scope=\"col\"| Class\n! scope=\"col\"| School\n! scope=\"col\"| Signing date\n|-\n|2\n|43\n|Cameron Cannon\n|Shortstop\n|R/R\n|4YR JR\n|[[Arizona Wildcats baseball|Arizona]]\n|June 12, 2019<ref name=TransJune>{{cite web |url=http://m.redsox.mlb